<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0001 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's PM, Sinn Fein Hold Constructive Talks in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
Monday called for more progress on the "demilitarization" of
Northern Ireland in the wake of the peace agreement struck two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with British Prime Minister Tony Blair in Downing
Street for 90 minutes, Adams also called for replacement of the
Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's Protestant-dominated
police force, by a "proper policing service."
</P>
<P>
But he said too much haste in the disarming of the Irish
Republican Army (IRA) and other guerrilla groups was not
realistic.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see all guns taken out of Irish politics, but we
don't expect the British army to disarm tomorrow morning, we don't
expect the Protestant paramilitaries to disarm, and I don't think
anyone should expect the IRA," said Adams, whose Sinn Fein party
is the political wing of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
Adams said his party still regarded it as unfair that the six
counties of Northern Ireland, with their majority Protestant
population who generally favor union with Britain, should be able
to veto unity.
</P>
<P>
But he added, "We think the next logical step in all of this is
for the British government to be encouraging, to be facilitating,
to be moving the whole situation in that direction."
</P>
<P>
Adams also said the meeting with Blair, under Sinn Fein's
request, was "positive and constructive."
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein will hold an annual party meeting on May 10 at which
it will decide whether the party will accept the peace accord
thrashed out by the eight political parties in the province.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Northern Ireland would get its own
parliamentary assembly, with power shared between the parties
according to their electoral strength. But there would be moves to
increase cross-border cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A referendum will be held on the peace agreement in both
Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic on May 22. Prime Minister
Blair is expected to go to Northern Ireland recently to campaign
for a "yes" vote for the deal which will end the 30-year conflict
in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
