<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Sells Olympic TV Rights to Canada and Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The IOC has sold TV rights to
the Canadian and African television for the 2000 Sydney Olympics,
announced Dick Pound, vice-president of IOC in Sydney on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the opening day of the IOC executive board
meeting, Pound said the Canadian rights for the next five Olympics
had been sold as part of a package to the Canadian Broadcasting
Corporation and two cable networks for 160 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The African rights to the Sydney Olympics fetched 12 million
U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleasantly surprised," Pound was quoted as saying. "The
Canadian Broadcasting Corporation has paid 28 million U.S. dollars
alone for the Sydney rights compared to 20.75 million U.S. dollars
for Atlanta and that was in prime time."
</P>
<P>
Pound said preliminary worldwide figures for this year's Nagano
Winter Olympics suggested the cumulative audience would match
Lillehammer's record 10.7 billion viewers.
</P>
<P>
He said figures were up in most countries but were down in the
United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
