<HEADLINE> Split Comoros Sends Envoy to Meet Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Special envoy from the Federal
Islamic Republic of the Comoros Islands Salimi Himidi Monday
conveyed Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe a message from
President Hamomed Taki Abdoulkarim on the current political
crisis facing the islands.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with the Zimbabewean president, Salimi Himidi
told reporters that he came to brief Mugabe in his capacity as
Chairman of both the Organisation of African Unity (OAU) and the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) organ on politics,
defense and security, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the OAU had already convened two meetings with
the government and representatives from the separatists involved
in the Comoros crisis in a bid to bring back peace and stability
to the Comoros, which is comprised of four islands.
</P>
<P>
Himidi, who is also Cabinet Director in Abdoulkarim's office,
said that the two meetings convened in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, and
the Comoros respectively resulted in the signing of an agreement
that would see the country holding a constitutional conference to
usher in a new dispensation to deal with the people's needs.
</P>
<P>
"One of the partners has since backed out. We expect this was
because of external pressure," he said. "We are still trying to
solve the separation crisis in one of the islands."
</P>
<P>
Last year, a separatist government was formed in one of the
islands, Anjouan, with the leaders of the self-declared state
announcing its secession from the Federal Islamic Republic of the
Comoros.
</P>
<P>
Led by Abdallah Ibrahim, the separatists claim that they have
been economically disadvantaged to the benefit of the government
based on Grande Comoro.
</P>
<P>
Himidi, on a similar mission to Mozambique, Tanzania and South
Africa to convey the same message to these countries' presidents,
said that it was almost apparent that a diplomatic drive to deal
with the Comoros issue had been completely exhausted, raising the
need for the OAU to send a conflict resolution mission or force
to help out.
</P>
<P>
"Something more than diplomacy may be envisaged at our next
African ministerial meeting on the issue and we hope the message
to President Mugabe will help in accelerating the need to bring
the crisis to an end," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
