<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Foreign Minister: U.S. Sanctions in the Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan admitted here Monday the United States is
contemplating fresh restrictions against the Khan Research
Laboratories (KRL) under U.S. laws pertaining to the missile
technology control regime.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said Pakistan would continue its
indigenous missile research and development program to meet any
threat to its security.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Assembly, he said Pakistan has
received indications from the U.S. administration that the latter
is contemplating fresh restrictions against Pakistan's missile
program.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was informed that these restrictions emanate from U.S.
internal processes under its national laws relating to imported
technology and not from the latest Ghauri missile test, he said.
</P>
<P>
During his recent visit to Pakistan, the U.S. president's
special envoy and U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations Bill
Richardson affirmed that the U.S. administration understood and
appreciated Pakistan's legitimate defense needs, Ayub Khan noted.
</P>
<P>
On the test firing of Ghauri, he said the Pakistani government,
after a careful strategic review, concluded that the test firing
of "our indigenously produced Ghauri missile was an essential
element of our research and development program that was vital for
Pakistan's security."
</P>
<P>
"This decision was made after due deliberations and careful
assessment," the foreign minister added.
</P>
<P>
On the possible U.S. sanctions, Ayub Khan said the application
of fresh restrictions "will have no practical implications" as
Pakistan is not a recipient of U.S. aid. "If, and when, these
restrictions are applied, these will be only against the KRL."
</P>
<P>
He also said Pakistan has already conveyed to the United States
"our serious concern regarding the action now being contemplated
by the U.S. administration against the KRL."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and the United States enjoy a cordial and friendly
relationship, Ayub Khan said, adding that "the relations of trust
and confidence between our governments and peoples have, however,
been strained by selective and discriminatory approach adopted by
the United States."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan would continue to engage constructively with the
United States "to build a new relationship based on shared
interests and mutually beneficial cooperation," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
