<HEADLINE> Volkswagen Raises Stakes in Fight for Rolls-Royce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The battle for control of
Britain's Rolls-Royce Motor Cars, the most prestigious motoring
marque in the world, between German companies Volkswagen (VW) and
BMW is set to intensify this week, said UK media reports Monday.
</P>
<P>
The battle lines were drawn up when the board of VW gave its
approval for an increased bid over the weekend as the deadline for
offer from BMW approaches Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It has already offered a bid of 370 million pounds (614.2
million U.S. dollars) and German press reports saied the board of
VW had approved an increased offer of 500 million pounds (830
million dollars) for the UK company.
</P>
<P>
Vickers, Rolls-Royce's owner, accepted BMW's 340 million pound
(564.4 million dollar) offer late last month and gave the German
group a 30-day exclusive negotiating period which will end
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
If BMW's offer had not been accepted by the deadline, the board
of Vickers would have to consider the VW offer.
</P>
<P>
However, Vickers was reported to be unable to comment on
reports of a higher offer from VW, saying, "We are currently in
exclusive negotiations with BMW, so we cannot comment."
</P>
<P>
BMW also refused to comment, but a spokesman repeated an
earlier threat that if its bid failed, it would cancel its
contract to supply engines to Rolls-Royce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
