<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, Canada to Increase Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Delegates from Quebec Province of
Canada Monday called for greater cooperation between Zimbabwe and
Canada in a bid to increase business links.
</P>
<P>
Addressing journalists after meeting Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe in Harare, Quebec Minister of International
Relations Sylvain Simard said the focus of their talks was on the
education and health sectors in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"The president and my delegation have agreed for better
cooperation so as to improve the trade between the two
countries," Simard said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the current economic problems that Zimbabwe was
experiencing, he said, it was generally a stable country.
</P>
<P>
The Canadians were optimistic that the country would be able
to overcome these problems and increase trade with Canada.
</P>
<P>
He said that they had also shared ideas on credit unions as
possible ways of helping up coming businesses and individuals
save money.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Zimbabwe was among the top group of countries which
conducted business with Canada with exports of different goods.
</P>
<P>
The 25-member delegation which came to Zimbabwe last week held
meetings with the ministers of higher education and technology,
and of health and child welfare.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zimbabwe and Canada intend to sign a memorandum of
agreement fostering mining and related activities, Secretary of
Mines, Environment and Tourism Charles Chipato said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement awaiting cabinet approval deals specifically
with the understanding on scientific, technical and
administrative cooperation in matters pertaining to the
administration of mining activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
