<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus: Turkish Cypriot Regime Not Recognized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said on Monday that
neither the United States nor Britain has the intention to
recognize the self-styled Turkish Cypriot regime in the north of
the Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
"No concrete proposal has been made either by the Americans or
the British on the recognition of the illegal state," Cypriot
government spokesman Christos Stylianides said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north in 1974 when Turkey landed
troops and took over the northern third in the aftermath of a
failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, the Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," recognized only
by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said there have been indications that the Turkish
Cypriot side has backed down from its demand for international
recognition as the precondition for resuming peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the Cypriot government wants "specific
indications" that the Turkish Cypriots are ready to participate in
talks, which are aimed at reunifying the island in a bicommunal
and bizonal federation.
</P>
<P>
This is something that the Cypriot government would see "in a
concrete and precise way" when the U.S. presidential emissary for
Cyprus Richard Holbrooke comes here, Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is expected here early next month in a bid to seek
ways to revive Cyprus' peace process, which has been deadlocked
since last summer when the European Union decided to list Cyprus
as a candidate for its membership.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of the talks
with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides in protest and insisted
that the intercommunal negotiations sponsored by the United
Nations be resumed on the basis of "two states." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
