<HEADLINE> WCC Attacked by Zimbabwean Christian Leader Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- President of Evangelical
Fellowship of Zimbabwe Andrew Wutawunashe Monday castigated the
World Council of Churches (WCC) for trying to use its December
convention as a forum to promote homosexualism, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a statement it was alarming that WCC, a
body which should be upholding biblical standards, was trying to
negate true Christian faith by turning the 12-day conference
scheduled to be held in Harare into a forum for gays and
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
"We roundly condemn such blatant perversion of the Christian
faith," he said. "We cry shame that it should be sanctioned by a
body claiming to represent Christians."
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the Zimbabwe Council of Churches to stick to
its previously scriptural stand on this issue and not be swayed
by international pressure so that Christians would not be forced
to boycott such an important convention.
</P>
<P>
While Pentecostal churches jointly condemned the move, local
mainstream churches have been divided over the issue of
participation by gays and lesbians at the assembly. 
</P>
