<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Talks Suspended Over Differences on Ulema </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The intra-Afghan talks went
into an apparent stalemate Monday as differences popped up between
the Islamic Taliban militia and their rival Northern Alliance over
the Ulema (religious scholars) Commission.
</P>
<P>
After the two sides concluded their second day of talks Monday
evening, James Ngobi, acting head of the U.N. Special Mission on
Afghanistan, said they had decided to suspend their discussion
until Tuesday afternoon and allow both sides to consult their
respective leaderships on the definition of the Ulema.
</P>
<P>
He said the Joint Steering Committee, which consists of five
Taliban and nine alliance delegates, discussed matters relating to
the proposed Ulema Commission during the fourth session of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee considered the definition of the Ulema
and finally decided to suspend its discussion and ask each side to
consult their respective leaderships on that topic.
</P>
<P>
"It will resume its discussion as soon as the result of those
consultations have been received, probably by Tuesday afternoon,"
Ngobi said. "The next session of the committee will take place at
3:30 p.m. Tuesday."
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan diplomat denied that the talks, which are being
jointly sponsored by the United Nations and the Organization of
the Islamic Conference, were deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
"There is no deadlock or anything like that," he declared.
</P>
<P>
When asked why the committee did not take up other items on the
agenda, he said it was because most of the time was devoted to the
Ulema topic.
</P>
<P>
And the committee "decided to use all the time between now and
Tuesday afternoon on this consultation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, head of the Northern Alliance delegation, Fazal Hadi
Shindawari, told Xinhua that "the talks were very fruitful."
</P>
<P>
When asked if they discussed cease-fire and the exchange of
prisoners of war besides the Ulema issue, he said: "We discussed
this issue, there was some progress and our discussion will
continue on this point Tuesday also."
</P>
<P>
On Monday morning, the two sides agreed on a four-point agenda
including the formation of the Ulema (religious scholar)
Commission and a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The Ulema Commission, proposed by the Taliban, would decide the
future political setup in Kabul if and when formed. The Joint
Steering Committee is yet another attempt to iron out the
differences between the Taliban and the Northern Alliance after
the former rejected the latter's first Ulema list in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
