<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deaths of Iraqi Children, Elderly Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The number of deaths among Iraq's
children and elderly has increased appallingly due to the U.N.
sanctions imposed since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, the
latest statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
According to Iraq's health ministry, 5,617 Iraqi children died
in March, compared with only 362 in the same month of 1989 before
the economic sanctions were put into place.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the figures showed, 2,215 old people in Iraq died in
March, up from 407 nine year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said most of the children died of diarrhea,
pneumonia and malnutrition, and the elderly of hypertension,
diabetes and malignant neoplasm.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the mounting death rate to the
shortages of food and medicine caused by the sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Term Economic Prospects in Asia Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The long-term economic prospects
for Asia remain bright, and would be made brighter still if
responsible steps were taken by Asian as well as other countries,
especially the U.S. and Japan, an annual conference was told here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the CGES (Center for Global Energy Studies) eighth
annual conference, Mike Bowlin, chairman of ARCO, said, "There are
some short-term obstacles, to be sure. The Asian flu will not
immediately disappear, and a lot of hard work will be required to
restructure the region's economy."
</P>
<P>
However, there is solid ground for optimism, given the signs of
renewed strength in the region, he said, adding, "A restoration of
confidence in Asia can't be achieved with an agreement, an
announcement or a promise."
</P>
<P>
"It has to be earned with actions, over time. We can see the
process underway in South Korea and Thailand, and fully expect it
to begin in earnest in Indonesia," Bowlin added.
</P>
<P>
In considering the Asia picture, the ARCO chairman said that
another issue, probably one that will require a more drastic and
long-term solution, "is the Japanese economy."
</P>
<P>
Japan is the dominant economy in the region. However, after 40
years of outstanding performance, the Japanese economy has
virtually stagnated in this decade. It has had flat growth this
year and there's little prospect of change for next year.
</P>
<P>
Bowlin said, "This is an economy requiring serious
restructuring. There is an immediate need for a substantial fiscal
expansion, and a need to address deep-rooted structural problems,
particularly in the financial sector."
</P>
<P>
As far as the U.S. is concerned, Bowlin said, if the Clinton
administration would find more "constructive ways" to restore
confidence in Asia, the Asian economic prospects "would be made
brighter." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
