<HEADLINE> EU to Enhance Closer Cooperation With Gulf States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will hold
ministerial talks with six Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
countries in London Wednesday in a bid to build a "strategic
partnership" between the two regions, said British officials
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing here Monday, British officials
said that the EU-GCC talks would focus on Iran, Iraq and the
stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
One British official said, "Our objective is to develop a
political dialogue and strengthen it to reflect what we think
should be a strategic partnership between the GCC and the EU."
</P>
<P>
"We hope the meeting will create a fuller and franker dialogue"
between the two important regions," he added.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that the London talks would pay
particular attention to Iraq, which is campaigning to have strict
international sanctions against Iraq lifted.
</P>
<P>
"We want discussions of how the GCC perceives Iraq and the
actions it's taking. I think we'll probably find there will be a
pretty close identity of views between the GCC and the EU," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The EU side will be represented by Britain, Luxembourg and
Austria -- the current, immediate past and future EU presidents
--, while the GCC comprises Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar,
the United Arab Emirates and Oman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
