<HEADLINE> Israeli PM Reiterates Determination to Withdraw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Following the latest casualties
of Israeli soldiers in South Lebanon, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu reiterated on Monday that Israel is determined
to withdraw its troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Netanyahu said that
Israeli cabinet's decision on conditional withdrawal from south
Lebanon, adopted on April 1, has drawn positive reactions in
the international community.
</P>
<P>
He said that security arrangements will be reached with
Lebanon, which will eventually lead to the peace between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made his remarks just after six Israeli soldiers
were wounded by a road-side bomb early Monday in the west sector
of the "security zone" in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that one soldier is still in serious condition.
And Hizbollah guerrilla group has claimed responsibility for the
attack.
</P>
<P>
Israel has announced that it will withdraw from the so-called
"security zone" in south Lebanon, set up in 1985 to protect its
northern border areas against guerrilla attacks, if it can reach a
security arrangement with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, Lebanese leaders have stated that Lebanon will not
provide Israel with security guarantees, saying that Israel should
withdraw its troops from south Lebanon without any conditions in
accordance with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
On the Israeli-Palestinian peace track, Netanyahu told Israel
Radio that he has been examining the American peace proposal even
the Palestinians have already accepted in principle the
U.S. initiative.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed that Israel will determine its security by
itself, saying that it is pointless to exert pressure on
Israel to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister did not elaborate on his latest talks with
the U.S. Middle East Peace Envoy Dennis Ross, who is currently in
the region to pave the way for the meetings between the
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Israeli and
Palestinians leaders next month in London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
