<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Opposes Splitting Term of 1st EU Central </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has
expressed his objection to a possible compromise to split the
eight-year term of the first European central bank (ECB) president
in order to end a EU dispute over the post, a German government
spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to German government spokesman Peter Hausmann, Kohl
would not accept a splitting of the term at the European Union
summit meeting on May 1-2 in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also confirmed a newspaper report that German
central bank president Hans Tietmeyer had sent a letter to Kohl to
express the bank's objection to such a speculated plan.
</P>
<P>
The German newspaper Bild am Sonntag reported Sunday that
Tietmeyer said in his letter to Kohl that the Bundesbank would
reconsider its recommendation on the single European currency euro
at its central council meeting Thursday, a day before European
leaders will meet to officially select countries to start the euro
in January next year.
</P>
<P>
Viewing the proposed compromise as a violation of the ECB's
independence, some Bundesbank council members have reportedly
threatened to reconsider their support for the euro project.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank, along with the German government and most other
EU nations, supports the former Dutch central bank chief, Wim
Duisenberg, to head the ECB which will set common monetary
policies for all euro member states. France, however, insists that
its own central bank chief, Jean-Claude Trichet, should assume the
powerful post.
</P>
<P>
It has been speculated that a "gentleman's agreement" might
have been reached under which Duisenberg, 63, would serve as the
first ECB president for the first four years and then give up the
post to Trichet, 55, for the second half of the term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
