<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Patient Jailed for Unprotected Sex in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A Cypriot woman AIDS patient was
sentenced to seven month imprisonment on Monday for placing her
sexual mates at the risk of contracting the lethal HIV.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old defendant Chryssavghi Zarzour pleaded guilty
before the Nicosia District Court of having unprotected sexual
intercourse with two men and not informing them of her disease.
</P>
<P>
After passing the ruling, Judge Haris Solomonides said that
strict and deterrent sentences should be imposed to protect
people's health from the increased danger of spreading AIDS in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Zarzour is a British-born Cypriot hairdresser and came to
Nicosia from London in 1987. She is the second person charged with
knowingly passing AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
Last July, Famagusta District Court sentenced fisherman Pavlos
Georgiou Kremastos to 15 months in jail for negligently passing
HIV to his British lover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Talks Bog Down on Ulema Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The intra-Afghan talks reached
an apparent stalemate Monday as the Islamic Taliban militia and
their rival Northern Alliance got bogged down in the definition of
the Ulema and decided to seek guidance from their respective
leaderships.
</P>
<P>
After the two sides concluded their second day of talks Monday
evening, James Ngobi, acting head of the U.N. Special Mission on
Afghanistan, said they had decided to suspend their discussion
until Tuesday afternoon, to use the time for consulting their
leaderships over the qualification of the Ulema.
</P>
<P>
During the three-hour-long fourth session beginning in the
afternoon, Ngobi said, the Joint Steering Committee, which
consists of five Taliban and nine alliance delegates, focused on
the topic of setting up the proposed Ulema Commission.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides agreed to refer contentious matters to
the Ulema Commission but they differed on the Ulema's definition.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, they decided to approach their respective
leaderships to seek clarification and guidance.
</P>
<P>
"It will resume its discussion as soon as the results of those
consultations have been received, probably by Tuesday afternoon,"
he said. "The next session of the committee will take place at
3:30 p.m. Tuesday."
</P>
<P>
However, the Ugandan diplomat denied that the talks, which are
being jointly sponsored by the United Nations and the Organization
of the Islamic Conference, are deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
"There is no deadlock or anything like that," he declared.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, head of the Northern Alliance delegation, Fazal Hadi
Shindawari, told Xinhua that "the talks were very fruitful."
</P>
<P>
When asked if they discussed cease-fire and the exchange of
POWs besides the Ulema issue, he said, "We discussed these issues,
there was some progress and our discussion will continue on this
point Tuesday also."
</P>
<P>
Another member of the alliance delegation, Rasool Talib, said
the two sides were getting closer to resolving their differences.
"The talks are heading toward positive direction," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, no Taliban representative spoke to reporters.
</P>
<P>
Monday morning's session of the talks produced a "positive
note" as the Taliban and the alliance agreed on a four-point
agenda including considerations on the formation of the Ulema
Commission, a cease-fire and the date and venue of the next
meeting of the steering committee.
</P>
<P>
But the suspension of the talks, the first encounter between
the two rival Afghan factions in over a year, has again cast a
shadow on the Afghan peace process. The Taliban and the alliance
met three times in Islamabad last year but they failed to make any
progress due to the inflexible positions of both sides.
</P>
<P>
The Ulema Commission, proposed by the Taliban, would decide the
future political setup in Kabul if and when formed. The Joint
Steering Committee is yet another attempt to iron out the
differences between the Taliban and the Northern Alliance after
the former rejected the latter's first Ulema list in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-Year-Old Burial Site Found in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A 2,000-year-old burial site has
been unearthed by accident in Lebanon's southern coastal city of
Sidon, the country's Future Television Station reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Construction workers found two three-meter-deep caves when
digging foundations last Thursday night, the TV said.
</P>
<P>
The caves lead to a five-by-six-meter hall with a
drawing-covered column at its entrance. The hall then branches
into several burial chambers.
</P>
<P>
The walls are covered with colored drawings, featuring
animals, birds and plants with golden, green, yellow and red
inscriptions.
</P>
<P>
Director general of antiquities of Ministry of Culture and
Higher Education Camille Asmar said the burial site is believed to
date back to the Roman period 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Work to deciphering the inscriptions has started to learn more
about the site, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sidon and the country's other several cities were once
inhabited by ancient Phoenicians and Romans 2,000 years ago. Many
historical sites have been unearthed in these areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0030 </DOCNO>
