<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gender Disparities Apparent in Africa: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Gender disparities are still
apparent in Africa, the United Nations Economic Commission for
Africa (ECA) has said in a publication entitled "Gender in
Africa".
</P>
<P>
Gender-differentiated resource allocation and prevailing
social norms prevent African women from playing their full role
in socio-economic development, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to "Gender in Africa", barriers to African women's
economic participation include:
</P>
<P>
-- Significant gender differences in education;
</P>
<P>
-- Obtaining credit is hampered by women's inability to
provide collateral;
</P>
<P>
--They are over-represented among the poor in Africa, and find
it harder than men to escape the poverty trap since their income
generating opportunities are few;
</P>
<P>
--In many countries they work longer hours than men on
agricultural and non-agricultural activities;
</P>
<P>
--Child rearing and housekeeping take up a large part of
women's time;
</P>
<P>
--Legal restrictions on women's employment, family life and
access to financial services leave little room for their
advancement;
</P>
<P>
--And food shortages, restricted access to health and welfare
services, insanitary conditions and low education levels manifest
themselves in higher morbidity among African women than men. More
girls than boys die young.
</P>
<P>
Now, more and more insighted people in Africa are clearly
aware that closing the gender gap is essential to achieve
sustainable growth in African nations.
</P>
<P>
According to the ECA, strategies have been made to eliminate
gender gap in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The five-point strategies include: promoting female education,
improving women's health and nutrition, increasing women farmers'
productivity, increasing women's participation of formal labour
markets and improving women's access to credit and other
financial facilities.
</P>
<P>
"Supporting a stronger role for African women will greatly
enhance their own lives, contribute to economic growth, improve
child survival and the health of all members of the family,
reduce fertility, and help slow population growth," ECA Executive
Secretary K.Y. Amoako pointed out in foreword of the "Gender in
Africa''.
</P>
<P>
At the close of the Fourth World Conference on Women held in
Beijing two years ago, governments adopted a global platform for
action.
</P>
<P>
This document reflects a new and important global consensus on
the need to promote gender equality and is an agenda for women's
empowerment, requiring immediate and concrete action by all.
</P>
<P>
Closing the gender gap, giving recognition to women's
developmental contributions and enhancing their participation in
all levels of leadership are essential not only for achieving
social justice, but also for reducing poverty and ensuring
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
An international conference, entitled "African Women and
Economic Development: Investing in Our Future" is expected to
open at the United Nations Conference Center here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 participants, including a number of heads of state
and government, African policy makers, United Nations,
organizations and specialized agencies, representatives of civil
society, and the donor community will attend the four-day
conference which is aimed at promoting the pivotal role of women
in Africa's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Women may "hold up half the sky" as the Chinese saying goes.
African women have played and are playing crucial roles in food
production, household maintenance and reproduction.
</P>
<P>
It is noteworthy that significant progress has been made in
improving the situation of African women since the independence
of African countries, especially in narrowing gender gaps in
major socio-economic indicators.
</P>
<P>
For example, women produce 75 percent of basic foodstuffs in
sub-Saharan Africa, process 100 percent of basic household
foodstuffs and meet 90 percent of household water and fuel needs
throughout Africa. They head over 60 percent of the households
in some parts of africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
