<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Shun Old Aircrafts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- African countries have been urged
to discourage the acquisition and operation of old and noisy
aircrafts by their airlines at the 15th plenary session of the
African Civil Aviation Commission (AFCAC).
</P>
<P>
This is necessary so that Africa will not become the junk-yard
of old and noisy aircrafts, the Nigerian News Agency quoted Ita
Udo-Imeh, the host country's aviation minister, as saying Friday
at the close of the week-long meeting in Nigerian capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Though the minister acknowledged the efforts by AFCAC states
to safe-guard the interests of African airlines in seeking
extension of time for them to continue operating old aircraft
types, he stressed that Africa should not be a perpetual seeker
for the use of unwanted or unacceptable aircraft types.
</P>
<P>
According to the Nigerian News Agency, the meeting in Abuja
admitted South Africa and Eritrea into AFCAC, bringing the
group's member states to 42.
</P>
<P>
Captain Shettima Abba-Gana, Commandant of the Nigeria College
of Aviation Technology in Zaria, Kaduna State, was re-elected
President of AFCAC for another three-year term.
</P>
<P>
AFCAC also discussed issues concerning the privatization of
the aeronautical industry, aviation security, training in civil
aviation and consequences of environmental policies and
globalization on air transport, according to the report by
Nigerian News Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
