<HEADLINE> China: IAEA's Work in Iraq Should Be Shifted to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China said Monday that the
U.N. Security Council should authorize the International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA) to end its wide-ranging investigations of
Iraq's nuclear program and shift its work to the monitoring phase.
</P>
<P>
Shen Guofang, Chinese deputy permanent representative to the
United Nations, made the remarks here Monday after the Security
Council was briefed by the IAEA on its report of the inspection of
Iraq's nuclear program in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Ambassador Shen said significant
progress has been made so far in Iraq's weapons inspection and the
Security Council should give a comprehensive and objective
evaluation of it.
</P>
<P>
Shen said China has noticed that in the past six months, the
IAEA has conducted many inspections and also participated in the
base-line visits of Iraq's presidential sites, during which no
prohibited materials, equipment or related activities were found.
</P>
<P>
China believes, Shen said, that Iraq has complied with the
obligations under Resolution 687 of the Security Council, and the
council should formally authorize the IAEA the transition from the
present stage to the next one, that is the monitoring phase.
</P>
</TEXT>
