<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks on Wall Street Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Heavy selling pulled down
sharply U.S. stock markets at midday Monday, triggered by fears
that interest rates could be headed higher soon.
</P>
<P>
Rising bond yields and steep declines in overseas markets added
to the pressure, contributing to what analysts called the
beginning of an expected market correction.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after 2:30 p.m. the Dow Jones industrial average
plummeted more than 200 points, or about 2 percent, to 8,864
points. On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues led
advancers by a wide margin of 2,768 to 218 as 253 million shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Other markets followed suit, with the Nasdaq Composite losing
62 points, or 3 percent, to 1,806. The S&AMP;P 500 index slipped 28,
or more than 2 percent, to 1,079.
</P>
<P>
The sell-off was triggered by sharp declines in bonds on the
heels of a Wall Street Journal article that said the U.S. Federal
Reserve has dropped its neutral monetary policy stance and is now
leaning toward raising interest rates. The story triggered a sharp
drop in the price of the 30-year Treasury bond, raising its yield
to 6.04 percent -- the highest in almost two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
