<HEADLINE> OA to Have Strategic Alliance With Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said Monday that Olympic Airways (OA), Greece's
national carrier, would have to enter into strategic alliance with
foreign airlines in the future in a bid to ensure its viability.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Reppas said the Greek government
was doing everything possible to make the national carrier's
revitalization plan a success.
</P>
<P>
He added that loss-making routes should be dealt with through
flight mergers.
</P>
<P>
The airline, which currently employs 7,250 people including 950
flight attendants, is estimated to have a debt of about 600
billion drachmas (about 1.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Greek parliament approved a bill tabled
by the government to restructure the debt-ridden national carrier
as part of its efforts to meet the targets for the European
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, the Greek government will be able to implement
its five-year plan to restructure the OA including a three-year
wage freeze and wage cuts totaling 5.5 billion drachmas (about
16.9 million dollars) as well as flexible working hours.
</P>
<P>
OA's pilots have since then been holding a work-to-rule protest
against the government's restructure plan, resulting in the delays
or cancellations of many domestic and international flights.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the OA administration appealed to pilots and cabin
crews to resume duties while the government warned that the
airline was in danger of closing if employees did not work towards
saving it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
