<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Reaffirms Support for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia reaffirmed
Monday its solid support for the Middle East peace process and
called on Israel to return occupied Arab territories in accordance
with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi position was made clear by King Fahd Bin Abdul Aziz
during a regular cabinet meeting Monday, a Saudi Press Agency
report said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said King Fahd pledged support for the Palestinian
people and their National Authority until their independent state
with Jerusalem as its capital is established.
</P>
<P>
The king's remarks coincide with the ongoing visit to the
region by U.S. peace coordinator Dennis Ross, who is trying to
bring the Palestinians and Israelis to terms on implementing their
signed accords in the run-up to the May 4 talks in London.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair who toured the Middle East
recently proposed to host talks in London among Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
U.S. State Secretary Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Monday's Saudi cabinet session tackled the outcome of Arafat's
visit to Saudi Arabia last week. He held talks with King Fahd and
Crown Prince Abdullah Bin Abdel Aziz on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has been critical of Israel's anti-Arab policies
and urged it to comply with the relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
