<HEADLINE> Egypt-Israel Summit to Focus on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Monday the stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace talks
will top the agenda of the Egypt-Israel summit.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the remarks one day before Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu arrives here for talks with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Egypt announced on Wednesday that Mubarak has invited Netanyahu
to visit Cairo during a telephone conversation to discuss the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
This will be Netanyahu's first visit to Egypt since last
May. Egypt has been critical of Israel's hardline policy on the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March,
1997 when Israel broke ground for the construction of Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as
the capital of a future independent state.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reports in Israeli media that the meeting will
also deal with Israel's offer to withdraw from south Lebanon,
Moussa said Egypt's stand in this respect is clear and will be
communicated to Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel decided to endorse the United Nations
Security Council Resolution 425, which calls for a unilateral
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon. But it demanded that security
arrangements be negotiated with the Lebanese government before any
troop pullback.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has expressed support for the stance of Lebanon and
Syria. The two countries have rejected Israel's offer, insisting
that the withdrawal be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it is high time that signed agreements be
respected," Moussa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
