<HEADLINE> S. Africa Ready to Help African Nations Tackle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is ready to
co-operate with other African nations in tackling their problems,
the country's ambassador to Tanzania Thandi Lujabe-Rankoe has
said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is ready to avail its resources and expertise to
help other countries address such problems as unemployment, poor
health care conditions and lack of clean drinking water, the
ambassador said during a dinner to mark South Africa's fourth
freedom anniversary on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
These problems are common to African countries, said the South
African ambassador to Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
During the dinner, attended by diplomats and dignitaries, she
said that Africa should enter the next millennium as a respected
member of the global village.
</P>
<P>
At the party, Tanzanian Minister of Home Affairs Ali Ameir
Mohammed said that despite implementation of the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund (IMF) policies, African states are
yet to make improvements in capital flows.
</P>
<P>
He called on African countries to implement policies geared to
increase real value of production and enhance economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Ameir said the freedom day anniversary is a very important
event for not only the South Africans, but the entire African
continent because it was the day the country gained its rightful
place among the African nations and the international community.
</P>
<P>
On internal affairs, the South African ambassador said her
country still suffers from high level of crimes, disclosing that
President Nelson Mandela is expected to launch a non-violence
project in South Africa as part of efforts to address the
problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
