<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Opposes Lifting of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States
acknowledges the progress Iraq has made in compliance with U.N.
nuclear investigations, but opposes the lifting of sanctions on
Iraq imposed following its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here Monday, U.S. Ambassador to the
United Nations Bill Richardson said Iraq has made progress in
providing U.N. inspection teams access to presidential and
sensitive sites, "but the overwhelming facts show that in order to
lift sanctions a variety of Security Council resolutions Iraq
still fails to comply with."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is on a one-day consultation Monday
reviewing whether it should lift sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq needs to make many many steps" before sanctions are
lifted, Richardson charged.
</P>
<P>
He accused Iraq of "hardly" making progress in the issues of
chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the inspections by the International Atomic
Energy Agency, Richardson said progress has been made in Iraq's
"nuclear enrichment, design, exports and concealment matters
regarding some of the nuclear operations."
</P>
<P>
But it's "premature" to close the nuclear file as the U.S. sees
a need for more progress to be made by Iraq in the disarmament
area, he said.
</P>
<P>
Disclosing that Russia has made a draft resolution to close the
nuclear file, he said it was not on the agenda of today's council
consultation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
