<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Again Rejects Palestinian Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- In celebrating Israel's 50th
anniversary as a state, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
Monday once again rejected the establishment of a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
Talking to Israel-based foreign reporters to mark the 50 years
of Israel's existence, Netanyahu said that Palestine can only be
allowed to exist as an autonomous region, not a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
has said on several occasions that he will announce the
establishment of the Palestinian state in May 1999, no matter the
peace process is progressed or not.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts between Israel and the Palestinians in the past
were great disasters not only for the Jewish people, but also for
the Arab people, the Palestinians in particular.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, however, blamed the Israeli-Arab conflicts on the
Arab refusal to accept the U.N. resolution concerning the
separation of Palestine 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Israel's troop redeployment in the West Bank,
Netanyahu said that Israel's condition is that the security of
Israel must be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Only Israel can make decisions on its security needs, he said,
apparently in an effort to justify his rejection of a U.S. plan
calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli troop withdrawal from the West
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
