<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Cuban Leader's Trial Call "Absurd" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday the call made by Cuban leader Fidel Castro for putting
organizers of the U.S. embargo of Cuba on trial is "absurd" and
acknowledged disagreement with Canada on policies to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Castro, in welcoming Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien to
Cuba on Sunday, called the U.S. embargo a "great crime" and
suggested the U.S. government should be taken to an international
court of law to stand trial as war criminals.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry, commenting on Canadian
Prime Minister Jean Chretien's visit to Cuba, acknowledged that
the 36-year-old U.S. policy of economically isolating Cuba had not
changed the island.
</P>
<P>
But he added it remained the best long-term strategy. "We think
over time it represents a better prospect for bringing about
change."
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Washington had made clear it did not agree with
Canada's policy of engagement as a way to encourage democracy in
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly understand their desire to achieve change through
engagement. We do not believe there is evidence that engagement
with Cuba has produced any change. They turn right around and say
that there's no evidence the embargo has produced any change
either," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We respectfully disagree about who's got the best strategy,"
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said Castro's calls for
the organizers of the embargo to be tried "are absurd."
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, the plight of the Cuban people, their economic
backwardness, is wholly the result of the economic system in place
for the last four decades," Foley told a news briefing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
