<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Existing Home Resales Climb Up to New Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The existing homes resales in
the United States shot up to a new record in March, surprisingly
climbing 2.5 percent, the National Association of Realtors
reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The monthly growth has pushed the resales to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 4.89 million units. The level breaks the
old record, a 4.77 million unit rate, which was created just the
month before. The rates are also the highest since the association
began compiling the data in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Based on the performance for the first quarter of the year,
Realtors President R. Layne Morrill predicted sales for all of
1998 would set a record.
</P>
<P>
The strong sales were attributed mainly to low mortgage rates,
which makes home-buying more affordable, as well as healthy income
gains fueled by the lowest unemployment since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
By region last month, sales rose 7.4 percent in the Northeast,
5.1 percent in the Midwest and 1.6 percent in the South. They
slipped 1 percent in the West.
</P>
<P>
In the country-wide, the median price for an existing home, was
127,000 U.S. dollars in March, up 5.8 percent from a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
