<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The sales volume of the "Gulf Coco Cola Company" have
increased by 92 percent over the past three years in Saudi Arabia,
the highest growth rate in the Middle East and north Africa
markets, Director of Public Relations Department of the company
Bashar El-Qadi said.
</P>
<P>
Having brought market share to 21 percent, Qadi said the
company expects a steady growth in market share in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The South African Standard Bank of London opened a
representation office in Dubai Saturday to monitor gold trading for
the Middle East, especially for Dubai.
</P>
<P>
A bank official attributed the opening of the office to
big rise in South Africa's gold exports to Dubai, registering
about 500,000 U.S. dollars last year. And South Africa has become
the second largest gold exporter to Dubai.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's gold exports jumped to 54.2 tonnes in 1997 from
13.3 tonnes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Statistics from Bahraini information and tourism
departments showed a big rise in hotel occupancy in 1997.
Sixty-one hotels of various grades registered an occupancy of 63.1
percent in 1997 from 52 percent in 1996, with an income 40.2 percent
up in 1997.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Statistics released by Jordanian anti-smoking society
show that Jordanians smoke billions of cigarettes a year with a
total cost of some 715 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Statistics say that 282 million dollars of the sum are spent on
purchasing cigarettes, and 433 million dollars go for treatment of
various disease caused by smoking.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of Jordanian smokers are male, 30 percent
female and 80 percent of those suffering from chest cancer are
smokers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
