<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The German Development Bank will provide Jordan with
5.12 million Jordanian dinars (about 7.23 million dollars) in
loans for building water projects in the coming years,
semi-official Jordan Times said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The money will finance a new sewage disposal plant in Irbid,
some 70 kilometers north of Amman, and two water projects for
increasing portable water supply in the Wadi Musa area, about 288
kilometers south of the capital, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Bank Leumi, the biggest bank in Israel, has gained
7.3 million dollars in profit in the first quarter of this year,
up 59 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The profit increase results from the bank's ongoing efforts to
streamline operations, including the merger of several branches.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Two of Israel's chemical companies, Makhteshim
company and Agan company, have agreed to merge as of next week.
And shares of the companies will then be traded on the Tel Aviv
Stock Exchange under the name of M.A. Industries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Italy has provided 67 million dollars in loans and 2.5
million dollars in grants for infrastructure projects in Lebanon,
the Daily Star reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-term loan with a 24-year grace period and an
interest of 0.5 percent, will finance projects in the country's
agricultural sector, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
