<HEADLINE> Peace Talks Between Sudanese Government, SPLA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between the Sudanese
government and the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA)
will be postponed to May 4 from April 30.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Daily Nation reported Monday that Sudanese Foreign
Minister Mustafa Osman affirmed that his government had received
word of the new date from Kenya, host of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
But the reason for the postponement is unknown yet.
</P>
<P>
"Sudan is keen to participate wholeheartedly in the coming
round of peace talks in Nairobi on the grounds that war has
proved to be an improper means for solving conflicts," the Sudan
News Agency quoted Osman as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to newspaper reports, the Sudanese Army predicted a
major rebel offensive in the south and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
General Abdul Rahman Siral Kethim was quoted as saying that
"Intensive troop concentrations have been monitored on Sudan's
southern borders, poised for an offensive in the coming days."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it was reported that Sudanese rebels had released
about 400 government soldiers from SPLA'S stronghold in Western
Equatoria Province.
</P>
<P>
The last round of talks between the Islamist government and
SPLA ended inconclusively in Kenya in November, 1997. The
government has been fighting the rebels since 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
