<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Upgrades Diuretics to Masking Agents Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, April 28 (Xinhua) -- An International Olympic Committee
(IOC) official said on Wednesday that it has upgraded diuretics to
the status of masking agents.
</P>
<P>
IOC Medical Commission Chairman Prince Alexandre de Merode said
diuretics could be used to mask other banned substances like
steroids.
</P>
<P>
Diuretics previously had their own category on the banned list.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission would also add insulin, which reportedly
boosts the muscle mass of athletes, to its banned list.
</P>
<P>
However, De Merode said diabetics would still be allowed to
compete and use insulin.
</P>
<P>
De Merode announced that drug-testing laboratories in Thailand
and Malaysia had been accredited ahead of major international
meets this year.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Games will be held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia,
in September, with the Asian Games in Bangkok, Thailand, in
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
