<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene dismissed
another high-ranking official on Tuesday over the prison escape of
a convicted child rapist and killer.
</P>
<P>
Dehaene, who dismissed his deputy prime minister -- who also
served as interior minister and justice minister -- over the
escape of Marc Dutroux, announced in a parliamentary session that
he was dismissing Willy Deridder, chief of the Belgian gendarmes.
</P>
<P>
Deridder had served in that post since November 1989.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was charged with raping and killing four of the six
young girls he abducted in mid 1996 when a nationwide child sex
ring was exposed.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties called for a vote of no confidence on
the current government and also demanded the prime minister resign.
(Belgium-Police Chief-Dismissal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Former Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme was
murdered by members of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK),
the Swedish media quoted a senior PKK leader as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Semdin Sakik, the Number 2 leader of the PKK, has been arrested
by Turkish authorities. Sakik said the assassination of Palme was
ordered by the PKK leader Abdullah Oecalan.
</P>
<P>
Sakik said the Swedish government's refusal to grant political
asylum to PKK members, and the fact that eight PKK members were
deported, triggered the assassination.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit told the press that
he would inform Stockholm of the most recent findings.
</P>
<P>
Palme was gunned down on a Stockholm street at midnight on
February 28, 1986. The investigation has been ongoing since then.
(Sweden-PKK-Palme)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban militia and their
rival Northern Alliance Tuesday accused each other of opposing
peace in their current round of talks being held in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
"We are not opposing the peace. We have already adopted an
agenda which includes formation of the Ulema Commission," Rasoor
Talib, member of the alliance delegation, told Xinhua when his
attention was drawn to a report broadcast by the Taliban-run Radio
 Shariat.
</P>
<P>
"There is different interpretation of the Ulema between (the
two sides). They've their own definition and we've another," said
Talib, representative of the Hezb-e-Wadhat, which is one of the
major alliance factions.
</P>
<P>
"They (Taliban) are blocking the road to peace, and we want
talks to move further," he said.
</P>
<P>
He quoted Abdul Waheel, head of the Taliban delegation, as
saying "my first proposal is my last proposal" in Monday's session
of talks. (Afghanistan-Peace Talks) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
