<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Urges Netanyahu to Accept U.S. Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Tuesday has urged visiting Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to accept a new U.S. peace initiative to revive the
long-stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak advised Netanyahu to respond positively to the
U.S. initiative which calls on Israel to hand over to the
Palestinians 13.1 percent more of the West Bank land over 12
weeks, a press release issued after their meeting said.
</P>
<P>
During their two-hour talks in the Al-Salem Palace here,
Mubarak reiterated that the only way to achieve progress in the
peace process is "strict implementation, in good faith, of all
agreements signed by the two parties, in particular the
implementation of credible further redeployments."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal "represents the minimum of what is necessary
to revive the peace process, especially in light of the positive
reaction of the Palestinian side," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross has met twice in the past
three days with Netanyahu to try to persuade him to accept the
U.S. proposal. But no progress has been made.
</P>
<P>
So far, Israeli government showed no sign that it would budge
from its rejection of anything more than a 9 percent pullback.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu is reportedly considering a 11 percent
pullback in exchange for Palestinian National Authority's (PNA)
promise to intensify fighting against terrorism and accelerate the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, on the other hand, have endorsed the proposal
in principle as a compromise and is demanding the U.S. pressure
Israel to accept the plan.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak expressed his conviction that a positive Israeli stance
would pave the way for the permanent status talks and facilitate
the resumption of peace negotiations on the Syrian and Lebanese
tracks, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
But apparently, the Mubarak-Netanyahu talks on Tuesday, their
fourth since Netanyahu took office two years ago, have failed to
soften Netanyahu's position in any measure.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu left for home immediately after the talks and no
press conference was given. This was interpreted as an indication
of a very tough meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace making has been stalled after
Israel broke ground for a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem
in March 1997 and deteriorated over the long-delayed Israeli troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Netanyahu summit came ahead of the May 4 four-way
London talks to seek ways of breaking the impasse in the Mideast
peace process. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
meet separately with Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat before the two can meet with each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
