<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Helps Kazakhstan Find Solutions for Nuclear Waste Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
allocated 223,200 U.S. dollars to help the government of
Kazakhstan assess the social, economic and environmental
consequences of unclear contamination at the former Soviet unclear
weapons test site near Semipalitinsk.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program (UNDP) Crisis Committee
made the allocation, a release from UNDP said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Assistance from UNDP and UN agencies will also help the
government develop an action plan to present to international
donors and train experts.
</P>
<P>
During the Soviet era, more than 500 nuclear and chemical
explosions occurred at the site. Some were several times more
powerful than the Hiroshima bomb.
</P>
<P>
Over 2 million people were affected by the resulting nuclear
and chemical contamination, which is blamed for birth defects and
abnormally high cancer rates. Infant mortality in the
Semipalitinsk area is 2.5 times higher than elsewhere in the
Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
