<HEADLINE> Philippine Navy, Coast Guard Look For Missing Malaysian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Rescue ships and aircraft of both
the Philippine Navy and Coast Guard were scouring the sea off the
southwestern island of Palawan to look for a missing Malaysian oil
tanker reportedly spotted near the area, the Coast Guard said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officer Edwin Pimones of the Philippine Coast Guard Fourth
District in Palawan said Coast Guard chief Rear Admiral Manuel de
Leon ordered the search-and-rescue operations after a mariner
sighted a tanker similar to the missing Malaysian oil tanker near
the Linapacan islet.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated oil tanker, declared missing on April 17 while on
its way from Singapore to Vietnam, was believed to have been
hijacked in the pirate-frequented South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
Pimones said de Leon also notified all sailors and fishermen
passing Palawan waters to immediately report to the nearest Coast
Guard and military stations if ever they find the tanker.
</P>
<P>
The tanker, carrying 1.5 million U.S. dollars worth of diesel
oil and kerosene, has 21 crew members, including seven Malaysians,
six Indonesians and a Filipino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
