<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Moves for Full Currency Convertibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China will continue its move to
achieve full convertibility of its currency, the Chinese yuan
(Renminbi), in defiance of the Asian financial crisis ripping
through Southeast Asian nations, a senior Chinese bank official
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"China will continue to move step by step towards full
convertibility of its currency," said Chen Yuan, governor of the
State Development Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a seminar convened to discuss the Asian
financial crisis before the Asian Development Bank (ADB) begins
its annual meeting in Geneva on April 29 to May 1.
</P>
<P>
"The process will not be slowed down due to the Asian financial
crisis," Chen said. "On the contrary, the crisis makes us realize
that we have to exert even greater effort in preparation for full
convertibility of China's currency."
</P>
<P>
He also invited more foreign financial institutions to open
offices in China.
</P>
<P>
As another sign of China's continuous economic opening, Chen
said, a package of tariff reduction plans has been submitted to
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The package specifies the details of the promise made by
President Jiang Zemin at the informal summit of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) in Vancouver last year, which includes
slashing the average tariff rate on industrial imports to 10
percent by the year 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
