<HEADLINE> Blair, Kohl Discuss Candidates of Future ECB Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
is expected to have a telephone conversation with German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl Tuesday in an effort to break the deadlock
over who will be first president of the European Central Bank
(ECB), according to Downing Street sources.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman told reporters Tuesday that the
telephone talks between Blair and Kohl would focus on the issue of
ECB presidency.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that most of the EU's 15 member states support
Wim Duisenberg, the Dutch president of the European Monetary
Institute, to head the ECB, while France has insisted that Bank of
France Governor Jean-Claude Trichet become the first ECB
president.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman indicated that the British government, the
current EU president, would be able to broker an agreement at this
weekend's special EU summit in Brussels. "It doesn't have to be
sorted out this weekend, but that is the desirable outcome," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed that Prime Minister Blair spoke by telephone
last week to French President Jacques Chirac and Dutch Prime
Minister Wim Kok over the row on the ECB chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
