<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Export Industry Faces Tough Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's export sector is
facing tough times ahead despite the government's efforts to seek
an export-led recovery.
</P>
<P>
An on-going seminar on "East Asia's Meltdown -- Life After
Death" noted that many hurdles remain for the export sector, not
only in Thailand but for all East Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
These hurdles include declining global demand, overcapacity in
some sectors and the region's intensifying competition.
</P>
<P>
The seminar quoted a forecast by the United Bank of Switzerland
as saying global demand growth this year would shrink to 3.3
percent compared with 4.4 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Stifled by the economic crisis and tight liquidity, Thailand
and other East Asian nations all hope that exports would generate
foreign exchange earnings to bring local economies back to growth.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, competition in the world market is intensifying
this year as East Asian nations flood the international market
with exports.
</P>
<P>
Former Bank of Thailand Governor Vijit Supinit said at the
seminar that structural adjustment in industry is now the crucial
challenge facing Thailand's export sector.
</P>
<P>
"The government has so far implemented structural adjustment
programs for the finance and banking sector. It is now time to
start thinking of restructuring the industry and real sector,"
Vijit said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Thailand is now gradually losing its export
competitiveness to other emerging markets and its competitiveness
ranking has slipped from 10th place to 39th in just one year.
</P>
<P>
Vijit said Thailand's economic crisis was spearheaded by the
sharp fall of export value, made worse by the cyclical downturn in
world demand for computers and parts, the world's economic
slowdown in general and finally the speculative attacks on the
baht, the country's currency.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the Thai economy would regain its stability
and equilibrium over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Poosana Premanoch, the former minister to the Prime
Minister's Office, said Thailand is now in the "stabilization
stage before a recovery."
</P>
<P>
He proposed that the government quickly stabilize the baht and
encourage banks and finance companies to recapitalize.
</P>
<P>
He added that negotiations with international creditors are
needed to settle Thailand's corporate foreign debts and to ensure
that relief is provided to the newly unemployed and a trade
financing scheme is set up for export industries.
</P>
<P>
"The government itself should play an intermediary role to
address the corporate foreign debts. A joint meeting between Thai
borrowers and foreign creditors should be held to discuss possible
loan relaxation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Poosana suggested that Thailand focus on its competitive
strength in agriculture and agro-industrial products and phase out
non-competitive industries to boost the country's export.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the establishment of a private investment
fund with government backing to invest in strategic industries and
corporations which are viable but lack liquidity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
