<HEADLINE> Christie's HK Auction Realizes 13M US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Christie's magnificent jewels
and watches sale in Hong Kong achieved an impressive 92.5 million
HK dollars (11.9 million U.S. dollars) Tuesday afternoon, becoming
the largest jewelry sale ever held in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The largest vivid pink diamond ever auctioned, a 3.2 carat
ring, also established a record price for colored diamonds sold at
auction in Asia when the London jeweler Graff bought it for 9.15
million HK dollars (1.2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Francois Curiel, international jewelry director of Christie's,
said: "At the time when there is a perception that the economy is
still recovering from the Asian financial crisis, I was thrilled
to see so many private buyers from South East Asia, which
represent almost 90 percent of the buyers by lot."
</P>
<P>
With the Fine Chinese Works of Art sale held in the morning
achieving 9.8 million HK dollars (1.3 million U.S. dollars),
Tuesday's sale realized a total of 102 million HK dollars (13.1
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Wednesday, the final day of Christie's three-day spring
auction, will feature the sale of jadeite jewelry. 
