<HEADLINE> Indian Prime Minister Outlines Economic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee outlined Tuesday his government's economic
policies aiming to make India a global economic power by the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
At the annual session of the Confederation of Indian Industry
here, Vajpayee presented a 13-point action plan for reviving the
depressed economy to achieve a 7-8 percent annual growth rate
before 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, foreign investment would be welcomed in all
areas of special priority including infrastructure development,
high technology, introduction of better management practices,
upgradation of product quality and critical global marketing
linkages.
</P>
<P>
The government would soon formulate transparent and
non-discriminatory foreign direct investment (FDI) policies, he
said, adding that the Foreign Investment Promotion Board would be
empowered to decide on FDI proposals.
</P>
<P>
A commission would also be established to review all
administrative laws, rules and regulations governing industry and
trade, and outmoded laws would either be scrapped or radically
simplified.
</P>
<P>
In his 45-minute address, Vajpayee also announced that the
Foreign Exchange Regulation Act would be replaced with a law
consistent with current needs.
</P>
<P>
The government would set up a national task force to draft a
national informatics policy to provide Indian business and
industry with an opportunity to become what he called "software
czars."
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said his government would play a more active role as a
legislator, facilitator and regulator and its relationship with
industry would be based on trust.
</P>
<P>
The government would substantially increase investment in
infrastructure development and private sector investment would
receive far greater policy and implementation support, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said that to avoid delay in the implementation of
projects in the power sector, the prime minister's office would
directly monitor projects capitalized at more than 1 billion
rupees (about 260 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"My office will seek a monthly progress report on all such
projects and ensure that they are completed and commissioned on
due dates," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
