<HEADLINE> Grachev Re-appears as Advisor to State Weapons Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Pavel Grachev, Russia's former
defense minister, has been appointed top military advisor to the
Russia Weapons Import and Export Company, said a company official
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Yevgeny Ananyev, director general of the company, released the
news of the appointment at a press conference. Grachev was
reportedly recommended for the position by President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
He added that Grachev, a man of great potential and wide
connections in the military field, will surely play an active role
in the company's future development.
</P>
<P>
Though beleaguered by economic intrigues related to the closure
of the Moscow National Bank, its financial agent, the Russia
Weapons Import and Export Company has remained Russia's biggest
weapon importer and exporter, and is responsible for 90 per cent
of Russia's weapons exports.
</P>
<P>
Grachev came in power as the defense minister of Russia in 1992
and was fired suddenly by Yeltsin in June 1996. 
</P>
