<HEADLINE> Business Community Voice Confidence in Hong Kong Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A leading commercial
institution of Hong Kong on Tuesday expressed its confidence in
continued economic improvement in Hong Kong this year.
</P>
<P>
James Pei-Chun Tien, chairman of the Hong Kong General Chamber
of Commerce, said at a press conference prior to the chamber's
annual general meeting that the overall GDP growth of Hong Kong in
1997 was "a creditable 5.2 percent" although the rate slowed to a
mere 2.3 percent in the last quarter.
</P>
<P>
Tien said 1998 will be a "tough year" for the business
community in Hong Kong but "there is no reason why we should not
see a significant economic improvement by the year's end."
</P>
<P>
Tien recognized that this year started "rather poorly" for the
Hong Kong economy -- external trade remains weak, consumer
spending was down, and the property and share markets are under
pressure -- and that it may take a longer period for the economy
to recover.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the opening months of the year were "notable
for some extremely positive signs" and "we are fortunate to see
GDP growth of between 1 and 2 percent in the first three months."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's "economic fundamentals are still sound and with
continued good growth on the mainland we should be able to ride
out the storm (financial crisis)," said the chamber chairman.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that interest rate would be
gradually lowered to the pre-crisis level.
</P>
<P>
Tien said the General Chamber of Commerce will continue to work
with and give full support to the Hong Kong Government to ensure a
better overall business environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
