<HEADLINE> PKK Leader Admits Killing Palme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Former Swedish Prime Minister
Olof Palme was murdered by members of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), the Swedish media quoted a senior PKK leader
as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Semdin Sakik, the Number 2 leader of the PKK, has been arrested
by Turkish authorities. Sakik said the assassination of Palme was
ordered by the PKK leader Abdullah Oecalan.
</P>
<P>
Sakik said the Swedish government's refusal to grant political
asylum to PKK members, and the fact that eight PKK members were
deported, triggered the assassination.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit told the press that
he would inform Stockholm of the most recent findings.
</P>
<P>
"Details of the assassination Sakik has described are
horrifying," Ecevit said.
</P>
<P>
Palme was gunned down on a Stockholm street at midnight on
February 28, 1986. The investigation has been ongoing since then.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish police had doubted that the PKK guerrilla
organization was involved in the killing. Authorities arrested
about 20 Kurds who were believed to be involved in the
assassination, but eventually released them because of
insufficient evidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
