<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Ends Visit to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General
Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid left the Algerian capital on Tuesday,
ending a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Abdel-Meguid held talks with Algerian leaders
on current developments in the Arab world, the dialog between Arab
and European countries and the issue of fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He warned at a press conference Monday that the Middle East
peace process is at a critical stage due to Israel's hardline
policies.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League calls for a fair and comprehensive Mideast
peace based on the relevant United Nations resolutions and the
land-for-peace principle, he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Israel's offer to withdraw from south Lebanon, he
said the U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 demands an
unconditional and immediate withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel decided to endorse the U.N. resolution. But
it attached the pullout with conditions that Lebanese government
guarantee the security of its northern border.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the offer, insisting that the withdrawal
be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Lockerbie issue, Abdel-Meguid said Libya is
in a good position after the U.N. International Court of Justice
ruled on February 27 that it has the authority to settle the
dispute between Libya, on the one side, and the United States and
Britain, on the other.
</P>
<P>
Two Libyans have been suspected of bombing a Pan Am jumbo jet
over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988, killing 270 people. Washington
and London insist that the two suspects be tried in either of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
But Libya, fearing that its citizens would not get a fair trial
in those countries, has refused to hand over the suspects. Instead
it proposed that they be tried in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
On the anti-terrorism issue, Abdel-Meguid said the Arab
Anti-Terrorism Agreement signed last Wednesday is "an enormous and
historic achievement" for the Arab world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
