<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Africa's ANC Mounts Attack on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- As the next general
election draws near, South Africa's ruling African National
Congress (ANC) has mounted its attack on opponents amid
opposition parties' outcry that ANC's intolerance toward
opposition is threatening multi-party democracy.
</P>
<P>
On the fourth anniversary of South Africa's freedom from
apartheid Monday, ANC leaders renewed their attack on elements
opposed to ANC-led democratic reforms and urged the government to
oust white officials who were "enemies of change."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a union congress in Durban, Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki said forces of the past "were still among us" and that
their agenda had not changed.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the fact that the present government had inherited
most of its structures from the former government, Mbeki said it
was imperative that the public service transform itself to become
more representative of the population, of which blacks account
for more than three quarters.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki suggested that a recent military intelligence report
warning of a plot by senior ANC members to overthrow the
government was aimed at getting the government to act against
itself and ANC's best former officials.
</P>
<P>
The report, presented to President Nelson Mandela in February
by defense force chief Georg Meiring, implicated top ANC members,
including Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, Defense Minister Joe Modise
and other former cadres of Umkhonto we Sizwe (MK), ANC's now
defunct military wing.
</P>
<P>
The report, later found to be fraudulent, triggered widespread
controversy and led to resignation of Meiring earlier this month.
Meiring was chief of the old South African Defense Force and
regarded by leftists as an obstacle to new defense force's
transformation.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said the enemies of change, arrogant and showing no
remorse for their wrong doings, have even "regrouped and
reorganized."
</P>
<P>
He referred to the South African Rugby Football Union (Sarfu)
which had sought a court order to set aside the appointment of a
judicial commission of inquiry into its affairs.
</P>
<P>
Hinting at Sarfu chief Louis Luyt, who insisted Mandela should
testify in court to explain his appointment of the commission,
Mbeki said that the enemies apparently felt strong enough to take
a man of Mandela's stature to court.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Mandela testified in court for the Sarfu case,
marking the first time a South African president appeared in
court to defend his executive decision.
</P>
<P>
Many saw Sarfu's demand for Mandela's appearance in court as
largely being aimed at humiliating the black national hero.
</P>
<P>
In another public address a week ago, Mbeki hit hard at
critics of government policies, saying that "enemies of
democracy" are desperate to spit on all efforts to create the new
order and to propagate lies to show that the democratic system is
failing.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Deputy Tourism and Environmental Affairs
Minister Peter Mokaba said the ANC-led government must remove all
"reactionary white bureaucrats" from senior positions and employ
skilled black people.
</P>
<P>
At a Freedom Day celebration in the Eastern Cape province,
Mokaba said white bureaucrats were opposed to the democratic
process under way in the country and that their leadership should
be replaced by "our own people."
</P>
<P>
"It is high time that we take our gloves off and fight back
against white bureaucrats whose intentions are to undermine the
ANC and its programs," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also called on people to vote ANC and to help it get a
two-thirds majority in the 1999 general elections so that some
clauses of the constitution could be changed.
</P>
<P>
His remarks contradicted Mandela's assurance last week that
the ANC would uphold the constitution even if it won a two-third
majority. Mandela said that the constitution was a collective
possession and anyone who works against it is "not being true to
the nation's founding principles."
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties Monday claimed that the ANC's recent
repeated attacks on the opposition and the press showed an
intolerant stance to criticism, which posed a serious threat to
the basis of democracy inaugurated in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
