<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Falls Sharply Against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso plunged
Tuesday, breaking through the important psychological level of 40
pesos per dollar amid mounting concerns over the forthcoming
presidential elections, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The average exchange rate between the peso and the dollar was
39.883 pesos for the day, up 2.7 percent from Monday's average of
38.817 pesos. It hit a high of 40.1 pesos within the first hour of
trading.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the sharp fall of the local currency to
mounting fears of political instability during the May 11
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
They said banks are buying dollars heavily in fear of political
uncertainty and a drop in investors confidence.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expected the peso to drop to as low as 42 to a dollar
in the run-up to the elections due to heavy demand for the dollar
and a tight dollar supply caused by the absence of offshore funds
in the financial system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
