<HEADLINE> Belgian PM Dismisses Another Official Over Dutroux Escape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc
Dehaene dismissed another high-ranking official on Tuesday over
the prison escape of a convicted child rapist and killer.
</P>
<P>
Dehaene, who dismissed his deputy prime minister -- who
also served as interior minister and justice minister -- over the
escape of Marc Dutroux, announced in a parliamentary session that
he was dismissing Willy Deridder, chief of the Belgian gendarmes.
</P>
<P>
Deridder had served in that post since November 1989.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian prime minister has nominated Louis Tobback to
replace outgoing Deputy Prime Minister and Interior Minister Johan
Vande Lanotte, and chosen Tony van Parys to replace outgoing
Justice Minister Stefaan de Clerck.
</P>
<P>
Vande Lanotte and de Clerck submitted their resignations last
week after the paedophile managed to escape from a court in
southeastern Belgium. He remained at large for more than three
hours before being shot and recaptured by police.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was charged with raping and killing four of the six
young girls he abducted in mid 1996 when a nationwide child sex
ring was exposed.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties called for a vote of no confidence on
the current government and also demanded the prime minister resign.
</P>
<P>
The no-confidence vote was expected to be held on Tuesday as
Dehaene had promised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
