<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians, Jordan to Discuss Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A Jordanian-Israeli-Palestinian
meeting is to be held in the coming two weeks to facilitate
Jordan's exports to these two countries, Israeli ambassador to
Jordan Odid Eran was quoted as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will concentrate on means to increase Jordanian
exports to the Palestinian self-rule areas as well as to Israel,
Eran said in an interview with Jordan's official news agency.
</P>
<P>
There are some "specifications" that limit the flow of goods
from Jordan to the Palestinian market, said Eran. But according to
the 1994 Paris Agreement, the Palestinian have the right to import
goods from Jordan and Egypt out of the frame of the Israeli
"jurisdiction."
</P>
<P>
During the upcoming tripartite meeting, representatives from
the three sides will seek ways within such a framework to help
Jordan export more commodities to the Palestinian area, Eran
added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Jordan's exports to Israel, Eran said they will
benefit from the rebuilding of the King Hussein Bridge which
serves as the border gate between the two countries and the
launching of Qualified Industrial Zone in Irbid where Israeli
products can be processed and exported duty free.
</P>
<P>
Israel is activating work in the fields of trade, transport,
tourism, communications, water and industries with Jordan, and the
upcoming tripartite meeting is just a part of it, he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been trying to maintain monopoly of the Palestinian
market which each year absorbs 2.7 billion to 4 billion
U.S. dollars of Israeli-made products, almost 95 percent of
Palestinians' total imports, according to the semi-official Jordan
Times.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Jordan and the Palestinians held rounds of talks to
ease bilateral trade and finally signed agreements on tourism and
product specifications. But the kingdom still fears that Israel
will hamper their trade exchange.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between Jordan and Israel stood at 35 million
dollars in 1997, which was considered as low by the Jordanian
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
