<HEADLINE> UN Conference Opens to Discuss Gender Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- An international conference
on "African Women and Economic Development: Investing in Our
Future" was opened at the U. N. Conference Center here Tuesday to
discuss gender issues.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi said issues revolving around questions of gender equality
have received increasing attention at the international level
since the 1975-1985 U.N. Decade for Women which was given further
impetus by the 1995 Beijing International Conference on Women.
</P>
<P>
"The effective and genuine promotion of gender equality and
the protection of the rights of women is, in the African context,
... inextricably bound up with commitment to grass-roots
democracy and their active participation in decision making at
various levels," Meles said.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference is convened to coincide with the 40th
anniversary of the founding of the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA).
</P>
<P>
Some 600 participants, including a number of heads of state
and government, African policy makers, U.N. organizations and
specialized agencies, representatives of civil society and donor
community are attending the conference.
</P>
<P>
Speaking also at the opening session, ECA Executive Secretary
K.Y. Amoako expressed his optimism on "a new era for Africa's
women", saying that "the good future of African women in
development depends upon women who see a different future for
themselves, with real opportunities, and with the odds shifting
more in their favor."
</P>
<P>
A new Africa requires a new gender partnership, he said,
adding that ECA has chosen Africa's gender issues as the single
greatest cross issue for its work.
</P>
<P>
The conference will deliberate issues on implementation of the
regional Dakar and Global Beijing Platforms of Action, which
place poverty reduction through the economic empowerment of women
as a top priority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
