<HEADLINE> CIS Customs Union Ends Moscow Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Interstate Council of the
four-nation Customs Union, at the conclusion of its one-day Moscow
meeting, vowed Tuesday to further relax border controls among
member states to ensure integration.
</P>
<P>
A statement entitled, "Ten Simple Steps for Ordinary People,"
was issued to simplify the procedure for acquiring citizenship,
for ensuring the free crossing of member-states' borders by
citizens, and creating favorable conditions for TV and radio
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
The Customs Union, a body grouping Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan
and Kyrgyzstan, commonly called "the group of four," has accepted
Tajikistan as a new member.
</P>
<P>
The five partners were also members of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS), a bloc formed by former Soviet Union
member-states to bid for economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Council also adopted a treaty on the legal status of
citizens of one country permanently living in the territory of
another country.
</P>
<P>
The participants in the Customs Union summit agreed to prepare
a draft treaty on the establishment of a single economic space for
the five member countries.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Union also decided to move the headquarters
of the Integration Committee from Moscow to Almaty, Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting of the Interstate Council of five members will
take place in Kazakhstan's capital Akmola on July 1-3.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin praised the results of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, Yeltsin said that "unlike other
sittings," the meeting in Moscow on Tuesday was quite dynamic.
With the admission of Tajikistan, "the volume of work will grow,
but so will the effect," Yeltsin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
