<HEADLINE> "Walk With Lions" to Come True in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Touring game parks in Africa, to
many, may be an experience of "caged men" in their vehicles
parading free animal world, but a new project here in Nairobi is
to free tourists from the cages and "walk with lions".
</P>
<P>
Just as the newly-shot Hollywood film "Walk with Lions" may
hint, the project, dubbed "Nairobi Safari Walk", is to bring men
and animals as close to their natural environment as possible,
David Western, Director of the Kenyan Wildlife Service told
Xinhua here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony for the Mini-Orphanage park,
a makeshift place for the building of the future "Nairobi Safari
Walk", Western said that the project would serve as a very good
education program for wildlife reservation in the country.
</P>
<P>
About 400,000 visitors are expected to come and view the new
para-natural park each year, Western said, adding that this would
be the most-visited park throughout the whole of Kenya, where
there are nearly 30 game parks.
</P>
<P>
The building of the project, the first of its kind in the
country, would take about 12 to 18 months, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Nairobi Safari Walk" is to be built on the current site of
the Nairobi Animal Orphanage which was established in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Originally served as a refuge for wild animals found abandoned
or injured throughout Kenya, the Nairobi Animal Orphanage has
taken in other animals, including non-Kenyan species as
chimpanzees and tigers, Western said, and the new idea is to
reshape it into a park between city and wilderness, and make it a
modern educational exhibition of live animals.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Wildlife Service director said that two classrooms
are to be built along with some other tourist facilities in the
Kenyan Safari Walk.
</P>
<P>
Visitors would move through a natural environment,
encountering animals as part of an unfolding tableau, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The new facility may attract wild animals to the Safari Walk
park, blending seamlessly with those in permanent exhibit areas
carefully crafted to appear part of the native landscape, he
said.
</P>
<P>
All development in the new park will be integrated into the
natural landscape of Nairobi National Park, the first wildlife
reserve in Kenya, which, just nine kilometers out of the capital
Nairobi, opened its gates to visitors in 1946, Western said.
</P>
<P>
Open savanna merged with bush, forest and wetland, would make
the animal habitat area in the park a natural world for the
animals originally housed in the zoo-like Nairobi Animal
Orphanage, Western said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
