<HEADLINE> Women and Science Conference Held in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 300 specialists
participated in a conference offered here by the European
Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European Union, to
explore the relationship between women and science.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference was aimed at assessing the reasons why
so few European women took an interest in science, and in devising
a plan of action to interest them in scientific careers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that only six out of every 100 engineering
students in the European Union are women, and although 70 percent of
medical or biological students are women, the figure falls to less
than 20 percent in physics and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
In Britain only one fifth of women with a science degree
actually pursued a science career in 1996, compared with 38 percent
of men.
</P>
<P>
European Commission officials say the fact that so few women
opt for a science career cannot be ignored when preparing to enter
the third millennium.
</P>
<P>
In order to redress the balance and promote equal opportunities
for women in the field of science, Commissioner Edith Cresson took
the initiative and organized the two-day conference in cooperation
with the European Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
Kuwait City -- According to latest Kuwaiti official
statistics, the growth rate of the economy averaged 4.2 percent
during the period from 1995 to 1997, while inflation rates during
the same period stood at 2.5 to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's oil revenues acount for 90 percent of the total
government revenues and more than 40 percent of the gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
Tehran -- During an international trade exhibition held in Iran
recently, Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Zanganeh said that his
country plans to set up 10 new petrochemical projects during the
coming four years. He said that these projects will cost 2.5
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh noted that Iran, the second biggest exporter of
petrochemicals in the Middle East, plans to treble its capacity
for producing petrochemicals so as to reach 30 million tonnes by
the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh -- Starting from May 1, Saudi Arabia will implement
the second phase of its plan to levy higher customs duties on
imported farm products.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the fist phase of the plan started last
February.
</P>
<P>
These measures are taken under a government decree raising
the customs duties on imported farm products by 25 percent in
season and by 12 percent out of season.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's unemployment rate continued to climb
this year and reached 8.3 percent in February, its highest level
since the end of 1993, the English daily The Jerusalem Post
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli Central Bureau of Statistic as
saying that the rise in the jobless rate has brought the
number of people out of work to more than 180,000.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted recently found that 72 percent of the
unemployed believe that the government is not doing enough to
solve the unemployment problem, and 86 percent do not believe
they will find jobs via the employment bureau.
</P>
<P>
In response to the rising unemployment rate, Israeli Finance
Minister Yaakov Neeman is going to introduce a job-generating
program soon.
</P>
<P>
The program will urge the government to impose hefty fines on
employers who take on illegal foreign workers. Neeman estimated
this week that the number of foreign workers without valid permits
in Israel is now over 160,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latest Standings of Whitbread Yachting Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Following are latest revised
positions in the Whitbread Round the World Race seventh leg in
Southampton, England, on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
1. Brunelsunergy, Netherlands, 20:59:39
