<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central, Western Regions Show Huge Export Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Local products from central and
western regions such as coke and vinegar from Shanxi Province,
cashmere from Inner Mongolia, fruit from Xinjiang, and motorcycles
from Chongqing Municipality are all favorite durings the ongoing
export commodity trade fair here.
</P>
<P>
For example, the coke of Shanxi, which is in ample supplies,
was sold at 90 U.S. dollars per ton at the fair, up from 74.9
U.S. dollars last year. The 20 varieties of Shanxi vinegar have
also sold well.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of the annual fair which opened on April
15, transactions of exports from the provinces of Anhui, Sichuan,
Hunan, Shanxi and Jiangxi, and Xinjiang Uygar Autonomous Region
rose sharply over last year.
</P>
<P>
"The good performance epitomizes the enhanced role of foreign
trade in the regional economy; it also shows the huge export
potential of these regions," said an official with the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China's foreign trade grew by 12 percent with a number
of regions achieving growth of over 20 percent, including 10
less-developed central and western provinces and regions.
</P>
<P>
The advantage of the products of the central and western
regions lies in their distinct local features, variety, good
quality and sales in small quantity, market analysts said.
</P>
<P>
"We can never neglect the importance of expanding the export
channel of the these regions," a trade official said.
</P>
<P>
The potential will be further tapped when an increasing number
of civil products made by previously military enterprises enter
into international markets.
</P>
<P>
The brand-name Changhong color television, for example, is
expected to make its debut at the export commodity fair this
autumn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
