<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's GDP to Grow 6 Percent: ADB Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's GDP (gross domestic
product) growth is expected to grow by 6 percent in the 1997-98
fiscal year ending on June 30, 1998, an Asian Development Bank
(ADB) report available here Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
The growth represents a slight rise from fiscal 1996-97, when
the country registered a 5.7 percent growth in its GDP, the
highest since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The report said that growth in agriculture may slow down in
1997-98, from a growth of 6 percent the previous year, while the
industry sector would rebound from its "disappointing
performance."
</P>
<P>
And the fiscal deficit, which accounted for 5.5 percent of the
country's GDP last year, is forecast to decline to about 5 percent
of the GDP in fiscal 1998-99, but will remain high this year as
the recent pay increase for the public sector will raise public
expenditure, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate in the country is expected to rise moderately to
5.5 percent this fiscal year from 3.9 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Both imports and exports will witness increases this fiscal
year, with the former expected to rise by 8 percent compared to 3
percent last year, and the latter to grow by 15 percent compared
to 13.7 percent in the 1996-97 financial year.
</P>
<P>
The report suggests that the Bangladeshi government develop
adequate infrastructure, including energy, roads, ports, and
telecommunications, to attract more foreign investment,
particularly in power generation, gas exploration,
telecommunications and cement production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
