<HEADLINE> East China Villages Moved to Guard against Possible Yellow River Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province has
moved some 180 villages easily flooded by the Yellow River to
safer areas, while some villages remain to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
A total of 105,800 villagers have been moved into new homes.
</P>
<P>
The province at the lower reaches of the river plans to move
the rest of the locals out of the flood-prone area by the end of
the year. The evacuation plan was implemented in 1996 with failure
to combating floods over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
For some villages that somehow cannot be evacuated, the
government will build a higher and more solid platform so that the
villages will not be inundated. 
</P>
