<HEADLINE> Zambia's Tourism Poised for Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's tourism industry is
poised for fast growth this year as investors have pledged to put
80 million U.S. Dollars in the industry.
</P>
<P>
Agness Seenka, Chief Executive of the Zambia National Tourist
Board (ZNTB), confirmed this here on Monday, Times of Zambia
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The national newspaper Times of Zambia Tuesday quoted Seenka
as saying that ZNTB has received a large number of applications
for setting up tourism enterprises across the country.
</P>
<P>
She attributed the sharp rise in the number of applications to
the on-going privatization of hotels and lodges.
</P>
<P>
The applicants are seeking to set up tourism enterprises
ranging from car hire, tour operation firms and travel agencies
mostly in the capital Lusaka and the southern city of
Livingstone, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said south African financial institutions have pledged to
finance projects aimed at improving infrastructure in game parks
of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambia's tourism sector will be well represented at
the Indaba Tourism Fair to be held next month in Durban, South
Africa, according to Tour Operators Association of Zambia (TOAZ).
</P>
<P>
At least 17 Zambian tourism-related companies, in addition to
the Tourism Council of Zambia and the Ministry of Tourism, have
confirmed their participation in the fair.
</P>
<P>
"By participating in the fair, we have a chance to meet with
international companies and market Zambia as well as the safaris
and lodges that exist here," said a TOAZ official.
</P>
<P>
Tourism earnings in the country continued to rise in recent
years and reached 62.7 million Dollars in 1997. 
</P>
