<HEADLINE> S. Africans Detained for Buying Leopards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Two South Africans who
bought three leopards from a game farmer appeared in a court in
Windhoek, Namibia last Friday on a charge of illegally
transporting or possessing a protected species.
</P>
<P>
South African citizen Willem Adriaan Nel and J. Knoesen were
arrested by Namibia's Police at a bar in Windhoek shortly after
midnight Thursday for having three leopards held in open cages on
the back of their bakkie, the Citizen paper here quoted informed
sources as reporting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses at the bar said the animals were being taunted by
people around the vehicle. Some threw cigarette butts at the
leopards, apparently to elicit a show of aggression.
</P>
<P>
Several foreign conservationists attending a conference in
Namibia also witnessed the animals' mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
Clarky McKay, Commanding Officer of Namibia said the arrested
South Africans bought the leopards without having the permit
required for the possession and transportation of the animals.
</P>
<P>
The South Africans paid 3,000 Rand (600 U.S. Dollars) for each
of the leopards. They were released on bail of 1,000 Rand (200
U.S. Dollars) each after they made a first appearance in the
Windhoek Magistrate's Court on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
