<HEADLINE> Dhaka Invests $7.88 Billion in Industry in Seven Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh invested 362.34 billion
taka (about 7.88 billion U.S. dollars) in the industrial sector
during the last seven fiscal years beginning fiscal 1990/91 (July
1-June 30), the Economic Times weekly reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was disclosed by Commerce and Industries Minister
Tofael Ahmed while answering a question in parliament recently.
</P>
<P>
The government had taken steps, including exempting income tax,
during the period to encourage foreign investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, foreign investors had been given guarantee
at the state level that their industrial units would not be
nationalized so that they could send their profit back to their
own countries.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed also told parliament that foreigners were enjoying the
facilities of setting up industrial units of 100 percent ownership
and setting up private export-processing zones.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh had signed bilateral agreements with 19 countries on
the protection of investment and business, he said.
</P>
<P>
Several laws had been amended to accelerate foreign investment
in the country and several departments had been established under
the laws, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
