<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Seeks Alternative Fish Fillets Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is seeking
alternative markets for the export of its fish fillets after the
European Union (EU) imposed a ban on the goods late last year out
of fear of cholera spread.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister of Natural Resources and Tourism Zakia
Meghji has said one potential market is Zimbabwe and that
consultations have been made during President Mkapa's visit to
that country last week, The Guardian reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The market is already there. But it is the question of
research," Meghji said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean experts will visit Tanzania to conduct a survey
before inking an agreement, she said.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the EU imposed a ban on export of fresh fish
fillets from east African countries on the shores of Lake
Victoria, the second largest freshwater lake in the world,
because of an outbreak of cholera there.
</P>
<P>
Fillets of the nutritious fish of Nile Perch which was
introduced into the lake in the 1960s have been attractive to
European countries. Tanzania used to export 13,000 tons of fish
fillets to the European market. Of the total, 7,000 tons were
fresh fish fillets while the other were frozen.
</P>
<P>
The embargo, if not lifted, will cause Tanzania a loss of 6.7
million U.S. Dollars a year, and has forced the country to seek
markets elsewhere. Apart from Zimbabwe, the minister said the
government is also finalizing plans to export fish fillets to
China, the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Meghji said the ministry has formed a committee to recommend
the best forms of fish exports. 
</P>
