<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Commerce Secretary on Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Mickey Kantor, the former
Secretary of Commerce of the United States, said here today
that the U.S. business community believes President Clinton's
scheduled visit to China will continue to build relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the successful visit to the United States by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin last year, Kantor, in an exclusive interview
with Xinhua, said that "the creation of a good atmosphere and the
policy of strategic cooperation between our two countries will
allow U.S. businesses to increase their involvement here in China,
which will be good for China and U.S. businesses alike."
</P>
<P>
Kantor, who was invited by the China Council for the Promotion
of International Trade, said he has learned that "great progress
has been made in many areas, including market access" during
negotiations between the United States and China on China's entry
into the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
He attributed the progress to the flexibility shown by the two
sides during the last few months, although "distribution and
agriculture are still of some concern."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Clinton administration supports China's
WTO entry on a commercially reasonable basis.
</P>
<P>
Of the financial crisis in Asia, Kantor said that China's
decision to refrain from devaluing its currency -- RMB -- has
helped avoid another round of devaluation in Asia, which was
"important for the stabilization of the Asian economic situation."
</P>
<P>
The currency decision was looked upon as an active and
responsible move and was welcomed in the financial community, he
said.  
</P>
