<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Chinese May Not All Originate From Peking Man: Scientist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese anthropologist has
offered a new explanation on the origin of modern Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"Modern Chinese may have developed separately from the south
and the north, and not all originated from Peking Man which lived
400,000-to-500,000 years ago in north China," said Zhang Zhenbiao,
a professor with the Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and
Paleoanthropology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Zhang inferred that modern northern Chinese may have evolved
from northern apes represented by Peking Man, and southern Chinese
may have developed from southern Asian apes represented by the
Yuanmou Man in Yunnan Province about 1.7 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, most previous research inferred that modern Chinese
all originated from Peking Man.
</P>
<P>
Zhang found that the difference between modern southern Chinese
and northern Chinese dates back more than 100,000 years after
analyzing the skulls in 36 regions dating from 200,000 years ago
to the present.
</P>
<P>
"At that time, the facial characteristics of modern Chinese
began to appear and could be basically divided into two types: the
south and the north," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The professor compared detailed measurements of the skulls and
the result showed that, if analyzed in two groups with the Yangtze
River as the boundary, the evolution of both the southern and
northern skulls are continuous.
</P>
<P>
"If not, there is an obvious discontinuity in evolution from
the early sapiens to the late sapiens, which could hardly be
explained," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, I infer that modern Chinese may not have developed
from the same near ancestor."
</P>
<P>
Zhang added that he could only infer the southern and northern
near ancestors of modern Chinese are the southern early sapiens
represented by the Maba Man in Guangdong Province and the northern
early sapiens represented by the Dali Man in Shaanxi Province and
the Jinniushan Man in Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
"And, before that, which apes they evoluted from needs further
research and cannot be decided yet," Zhang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0131 </DOCNO>
