<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Share prices made a U-turn on
the Singapore market on Tuesday, losing grounds in the morning
session, but recovering in the afternoon, with the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) gaining 10.3 points to
close at 1,481.77 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that the overnight fall on Wall Street dealt a
blow to buying sentiment in early dealings. But traders said
prices edged up later on renewed talk that local banks are
planning to lower their interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Investors were also encouraged by the stability of the regional
currencies, the dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased slightly to 164.82 million
units, valued at 216.4 million Singapore dollars (about 135.25
million US dollars). Advances overtook declines by 193 to 128,
while 275 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
RHB Capital Warrant99 was the most actively traded counter as
it registered a turnover of 15.99 million units. It was followed
by Rekapac which had 9.69 million shares traded. Easyknit was next
with 8.1 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
OUB (Overseas Union Bank) Foreign and UOB (United Overseas
Bank) Foreign shared the top spot on the gainers' list as each of
them rose by 45 cents to finish at 6.25 and 7.65 Singapore dollars
respectively. Creative 50 increased by 40 cents to end at 32.8
Singapore dollars, while OCBC (Overseas Chinese Banking
Corporation) Foreign was up by 35 cents to close at 8.2 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Transmarco was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.8 dollars to end at 6.2 Singapore dollars. Bukit
Sembawang fell by 50 cents to close at 10.8 Singapore dollars.
Prima lost 21 cents to finish at 2.87 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
