<HEADLINE> EU to Lift 'Non-Market Economy' Label from China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China today welcomed news that an
agreement reached by foreign ministers of the European Union (EU)
on Monday would remove the "non-market economy" status label on
China.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao told a news briefing
here today that the Council of Ministers of the European Union
approved the proposals set forth by the EU Commission on December
16, 1997, and has decided to remove the "non-market economy"
status label from China.
</P>
<P>
"This move is a step forward by the European Union in revising
its anti-dumping policies against China and will have a positive
impact on the smooth development of Sino-European economic and
trade relations," said Zhu, "so, we welcome it."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman said, "We also hope that the EU can
view all Chinese enterprises equally without any discrimination
and extend a completely fair and equal treatment to them."
</P>
