<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordan Trade Organization (JTA) is to hold a
six-day industrial fair in Gaza starting from May 7 to orient the
Palestinian public on the kingdom's products, English daily Jordan
Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Displayed on the fair will be goods ranging from electric and
telecommunications equipment to foodstuff and domestic products.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Jordan exported some 15.1 million U.S. dollars worth
of products to the Palestinian self-rule areas while imported 30.6
million dollars worth of Palestinian goods.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Bank of Israel will cut the key lending rate
by 0.3 percentage points to 11.9 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The lending rate cut, one in a series in recent months, makes
money a little easier to borrow in a sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman will fly to
Washington next week to arrange the final details of the plan to
end the U.S. civilian aid to Israel within the next decade.
</P>
<P>
During his visit in Washington, Neeman will also ask the
U.S. to increase military assistance to Israel.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Energy officials from Turkey, Azerbaijan and Georgia
will hold talks in Istanbul, the largest city in Turkey, from May
5 to 6 on the Baku-Ceyhan pipeline, Turkish Daily News reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The officials are expected to exchange views over the issues of
the pipeline construction aimed at exploiting the abundant Caspian
oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The planned pipeline from Azerbaijani capital of Baku to the
southern Turkish city of Ceyhan, which has 468 kilometers in
Azerbaijan, 225 kilometers in Georgia and 1,037 kilometers in
Turkey, is of great significance to the three countries' energy
industries, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by German experts and financed by the World
Bank put the total cost of the project at around 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
If completed, the pipeline is expected to have a capacity of
45 million tonness per year and the figure can be raised in the
future, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
