<HEADLINE> China, Kyrghyz Sign Joint Statement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China and the Kyrghyz Republic
will make concerted efforts to promote bilateral friendly relations
of cooperation to a new high, according to a joint statement made
public today.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed Monday by President Jiang Zemin and his
counterpart, Kyrghyz's Askar Akayevich Akayev, said this
agreement is based on traditional friendship and their common
aspirations to further promote good-neighborly cooperative ties of
mutual interest in a long-term and stable manner.
</P>
<P>
Both countries reiterated in the joint statement that they will
strictly observe the documents signed on bilateral relations in
1992 and 1996 and further expand cooperation in the fields of
politics, economy, trade, military affairs, science, technology,
culture, education, tourism and sports.
</P>
<P>
They will continue the political dialogues including the
different levels of exchanges of visits, further strengthening
mutual trust and understanding, and solving problems according to
the international norms and on the basis of good will and mutual
interest.
</P>
<P>
Both sides will follow closely the border agreement signed on
July 4, 1996 and start the demarcation work on the agreed
border. At the same time, the direction of the remaining border
will be fixed through negotiations in a bid to solve in a thorough
and final way the border issue between the two countries on the
basis of the current border agreement and in the spirit of equal
consultation, mutual understanding and accommodation, and
international norms.
</P>
</TEXT>
