<HEADLINE> S'pore Manufacturing Output Up 6.1 Pct in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's manufacturing
output in the first quarter of this year grew by 6.1 percent from
a year ago, partly because of the low base in 1997 and the fast
growth in the pharmaceutical segment, the Economic Development
Board (EDB) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that for the same reasons, the manufacturing output in
March increased by eight percent.
</P>
<P>
The EDB said the pharmaceutical industry grew by 106.5 percent
compared to March last year, boosted by the production of high
value added pharmaceuticals by an existing company and increased
capacity in a new plant. Cumulative output for the first quarter
of 1998 rose by 22.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The output of the electronic cluster rose by 4.5 percent in
March. There was significant growth in semiconductors arising from
increased U.S. sales and in comparison with the weak base last
year when the semiconductor segment was in the slump.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative output for the electronics cluster registered a
4.6 percent increase in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The chemicals cluster, including petroleum, petrochemicals,
pharmaceuticals and specialty chemicals, recorded a year-on-year
growth of 31.8 percent in March, with increases coming from the
pharmaceuticals, petroleum and petrochemicals segments.
</P>
<P>
The output of the engineering cluster increased by 11.5 percent
in March with the transport engineering segment recording
substantial growth. The cumulative output for the first quarter
grew by 13.3 percent compared to the same period of 1997, the EDB
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
