<HEADLINE> China, Kyrghyz Sign Joint Statement (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two will continue to support border contacts and
cooperation, which they think is an important part of the
China-Kyrghyz good-neighborly cooperation of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
Both sides will further strengthen their cooperation to fight
international terrorism, trans-country organized crime,
trafficking and smuggling of arms and drugs, economic crimes and
other forms of crime.
</P>
<P>
They plan to oppose any form of separatism and will not allow
any organization or force in their respective country to have
separatist undertakings targeted at the other. They also plan to
tighten cooperation in this field.
</P>
<P>
Kyrghyzstan reiterated that the government of the People's
Republic of China is the sole legal government and Taiwan is part
of China, and that it will not establish official relations in any
form with Taiwan or undertake any official contact.
</P>
<P>
China re-stated that it supports Kyrghyzstan's efforts in
safeguarding its independence, sovereignty and territorial
integrity, and in developing and consolidating the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are ready to strengthen consultations and
cooperation in the United Nations and other international
organizations on issues of common concern in a bid to establish a
peaceful, stable, fair, reasonable and new international political
and economic order to safeguard world peace and promote the
development of mankind.
</P>
<P>
China said it appreciates Kyrghyzstan's efforts in
strengthening regional stability and cooperation, while
Kyrghyzstan spoke highly of China's efforts to increase mutual
trust and beneficial cooperation among neighboring nations.
</P>
<P>
Kyrghyzstan also expressed its hope that China would support
its proposal at the U.N. Congress that U.N.-presided peace talks
on the Afghanistan issue should be held at Bischkek, and the
establishment of a nuclear-free Central Asia.  
</P>
