<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Factions Trade Accusations on Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban
militia and their rival Northern Alliance Tuesday accused each
other of opposing peace in their current round of talks being held
in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
"We are not opposing the peace. We have already adopted an
agenda which includes formation of the Ulema Commission," Rasoor
Talib, member of the alliance delegation, told Xinhua when his
attention was drawn to a report broadcast by the Taliban-run Radio
Shariat.
</P>
<P>
"There is different interpretation of the Ulema between (the
two sides). They've their own definition and we've another," said
Talib, representative of the Hezb-e-Wadhat, which is one of the
major alliance factions.
</P>
<P>
"They (Taliban) are blocking the road to peace, and we want
talks to move further," he said.
</P>
<P>
He quoted Abdul Waheel, head of the Taliban delegation, as
saying "my first proposal is my last proposal" in Monday's session
of talks.
</P>
<P>
"This means they (Taliban) don't believe in consultations,"
Talib said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Radio Shariat declared that "the opposition
delegation are not ready to accept the Ulema Commission."
</P>
<P>
The radio said that the alliance representatives had reversed
an earlier stand and now opposed the formation of the Ulema
Commission to solve the country's protracted conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Steering Committee talks, which started on Sunday, were
suspended Monday to enable both delegations to consult with their
top leaders over the issue of who should be qualified to sit on
the proposed Ulema Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Steering Committee, made up of five Taliban and nine
alliance delegates, is to resume its talks Tuesday afternoon,
announced James Ngobi, acting head of the U.N. Special Mission on
Afghanistan, Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
During their morning session on Monday, the two sides agreed on
a four-point agenda which includes formation of the Ulema
Commission, a ceasefire, an exchange of POWs and the date and
venue of the next Steering Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
The talks, the first face-to-face formal encounter between the
Taliban and the Northern Alliance in more than a year, are being
sponsored by the United Nations and the Organization of the
Islamic Conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
