<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Disasters Cause 1.5 Billion Yuan in Losses for 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Fire disasters cost China 1.54
billion yuan (186 million U.S. dollars) in 1997, doubling that of
five years ago, a senior official with the Ministry of Public
Security said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, more than 300,000 fires claimed 12,368
lives and injured 22,382 people in China, said Sun Lun, chief of
the Ministry's Fire Control Bureau, who was attending the ongoing
Second Session of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC) which will end Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There were 88 disastrous conflagrations which left at least 10
dead and 20 severely injured each, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
The five-year loss for the nation and the people was 6 billion
yuan, said Sun, adding that authorities urgently need to propose a
law on fire control.
</P>
<P>
Some 320 people lost their lives and another 120 were injured
in a fire at a disco hall in northeastern Liaoning Province years
ago, sources from the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
China has had fire control regulations for 14 years, experts
said, however, the existing regulations cannot help reduce fires
and prevent them from happening.
</P>
<P>
The draft of a Law on Fire Control has been deliberated by the
NPC Standing Committee several times.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the draft might be approved in the
current session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
