<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Call for Profound Changes in Higher Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Senior Chinese legislators said
today that China's higher education system must undergo profound
changes to meet the national goal of revitalizing the country with
science and education.
</P>
<P>
Deliberating the draft Law on Higher Education at the ongoing
second session of the National People's Congress (NPC) Standing
Committee, many lawmakers offered sharp comments on the system,
saying that the present system has lagged far behind the country's
economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
In a country with a population of over 1.2 billion, there are
only 2,000 universities and colleges in China which enroll 5.67
million students.
</P>
<P>
Lawmaker Shen Jingzhu said that various types of institutions
of higher learning can be set up which can be run by the central,
provincial and municipal governments and individuals.
</P>
<P>
"There are too few higher education institutions in China, so
it is hard to change the present examination-oriented system with
such number and mechanism of the institutions," Shen said.
</P>
<P>
Many university presidents have to be engrossed in obtaining
funds instead of concentrating on teaching, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
Lawmaker Jiang Shusheng said that after the institutional
restructuring of the State Council, some universities and colleges
should detach themselves from the ministries and commissions of
the State Council.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the founding of an intermediatory organization
responsible for allocating funds to higher educational
institutions to coordinate their teaching and research.
</P>
<P>
The majority of colleges and universities which used to be run
by the ministries and commissions of the State Council can be run
by provincial governments, but some high-quality ones should
remain under the overall management of the Ministry of Education,
the lawmaker said.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft law, the state encourages enterprises,
social organizations and citizens to manage institutions of higher
learning. However, fiscal appropriation will remain the main
channel of funding universities and colleges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
