<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Plunging in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued tumbling in
Tokyo Tuesday with the key Nikkei index ending below the 15,500
level for the first time since January 14, on selling triggered by
overnight declines in New York stock prices and Chicago Nikkei
futures.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the
First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 254.52 points, or
1.63 percent from Monday's close to 15,395.43.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, declined 12.92 points, or 1.06 percent to
1,200.90.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section went up to an estimated 400 million
shares from Monday's 320 million.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The key Dow Jones Industrial Average on Wall Street fell 146.98
points to finish at 8,917.64 on large sell-off triggered by
worries that the U.S. Federal Reserve Board would raise interest
rates later this year.
</P>
<P>
On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the key June Nikkei futures
contract plummeted 335 points to close at 15,265.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo investors, shocked by the overseas movements, actively
placed sell orders, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,328 First Section issues, losers outnumbered gainers
910 to 266, with 152 remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
