<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- French Minister of Education Claude Allegre has decided to
reduce the weekly school hours in high schools to 35 hours, in
order to let high school students "learn less but learn better."
</P>
<P>
-- Winning 12.9 percent of the votes in the regional election
of Saxony-Anhalt, the German People's Union (DVU) obtained the
biggest victory of the extreme-right in Germany since the end of
the war.
</P>
<P>
Stefan Schieren, a professor of Magdeburg, said that the
extreme-right could continue to expand in eastern Germany, as
nearly one third of the people there are deeply sceptical about
the parliamentary system, democracy and market economy imported
from the west after reunification.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The defeat on Sunday of the mainstream rightwing candidates
for the local parliament in Toulon, southern France, reflected the
weakening and disarray within the rightwing RPR and UDF. A
socialist candidate and a candidate from the extreme-right
National Front will compete each other in the run-off next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a latest poll shows that 53 percent of the French
people consider the FN as a party different in nature from others.
</P>
<P>
-- The tension over interest rates in the United States and
Germany and the uncertainty over the nomination of president of the
European Central Bank have made the major stock indexes in Europe
and the United States fall on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
