<HEADLINE> 35 Reportedly Killed in Floods in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-five people had been
killed in the heavy flooding in eastern Afghanistan, and the
western and central parts of the war-ravaged country were also
badly hit by heavy spring rains, said reports monitored here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Radio Shariat, controlled by the Islamic
Taliban militia, announced the death of 35 people in Paich and
Asmar districts of the eastern Kunar province and said 14,800
acres of farm land had also been "washed away."
</P>
<P>
The radio, the mouthpiece of the Taliban, also reported that
some 300 houses had been destroyed by floods in Qarshi district of
the western Herat province. It said 30 percent of crops had been
destroyed and 1,000 cattle killed.
</P>
<P>
Heavy flooding had also hit some districts of the central
mountainous Shiite Muslim populated Hazarajat region, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Heavy floods hit Afghanistan after a rapid spring thaw
following an icy and snow-bound winter. Heavy spring rains have
also struck mountainous areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
