<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Route Linking Highest Airport Achieves Safety Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China Southwest Airlines
announced today it has achieved three years of safe operations
between Chengdu in southwest China's Sichuan Province and Bangda
Airport of Changdu in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The Bangda Airport of Changdu on the "roof of the world," the
Tibetan Plateau, is the world's highest airport. It is 4,334
meters above sea level, and the air route connecting it is
considered by the world's civil aviation industry as the most
difficult.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Bo, spokesman for the airline, the launch of
the Chengdu-Changdu route three years ago was "another wonder in
civil aviation history after the opening of the Chengdu-Lhasa
route," and terminated the city's total dependence on highway
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Changdu, halfway on the Sichuan-Tibet Highway, is a political
and cultural center of eastern Tibet. It took five days to reach
either end of the highway, Chengdu or Lhasa, before the air
passage was available.
</P>
<P>
In the last three years, 414 flights in Boeing 757 series
have safely transported 37,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
Faced with unfavorable flying conditions, including constant
weather changes and complicated geography, Southwest Airlines
conducts the highest safety management system, special plane
standard, between Chengdu and Changdu. Each flight has two
captains on board.
</P>
<P>
The airline has not recorded an accident during its 42-year
performance on the route connecting the Tibetan Plateau with the
outside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
