<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarket Continues Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market lost
1.3 percent Tuesday to close at its lowest level since April 3,
after fears of a rate increase in the United States and lower
Asian markets sapped confidence.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 36.7 points lower at 2,781.3, but
off lows of 2,763.1 in late trade.
</P>
<P>
"The fall was on the back of Wall Street and concerns about
interest rate rises. The weakness in the Asian markets during the
day has perpetuated that," Steve Mayne from Nevitts said.
</P>
<P>
"A US interest rate rise is more and more of a possibility and
there is less likelihood there will be a rate cut here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Locally, banking stocks were sold off on the interest rate
prospects, with National Australia Bank's 67.2 cent fall, the
largest drop of the majors. ANZ fell 30.6 cents, Commonwealth
dropped 19.2 while Westpac was steady at 10.60 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking index fell 1.73 percent or 102.7 points to 5,838.7,
while the all industrials index finished 1.38 percent or 66.3
points lower at 4,746.4.
</P>
<P>
News Corp ordinary shares lost 19.7 cents to 10.227 Australian
dollars while the Preferreds shed 20 to 8.70 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Patrick stevedores parent Lang Corp lost another 10 cents to
1.65 Australian dollars as the market awaited the outcome of its
High Court battle with the Maritime Union of Australia.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 12.5 points weaker at 1,217.1,
with the gold sector weaker on a falling bullion price.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 3.3 percent or 45.5 points to 1,328.1,
as the bullion price tumbled 2.75 per ounce to 308.90 U.S. dollars
in late Sydney trade.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 312.52 million shares at a value of
908.01 million Australian dollars (590.2 million U.S. dollars)
with falls outnumbering rises by 826 to 349. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
