<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Policy Adjusted To Cope With Changing Global Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China is adjusting its export
policy to offset the negative influence of the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the financial crisis in Southeast Asia,
China has been confronted with declining exports to this region
and the increasing competitive pressure of cheaper products from
neighboring countries for export to Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, China has not only expanded its
market share in Europe and North America but also built up trade
ties with customers in the Commonwealth of Independent States,
Eastern Europe, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The policy of multi-outlet international markets and optimizing
the structure of exports has paid off at the 83rd Guangzhou
Commodity Export Trade Fair, which is being held in south China's
Guangdong Province, said Liu Xiangdong, assistant minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
So far, the transaction volume of the current trade fair has
exceeded the expectations of Chinese exporters. Both the number of
traders and orders have set all-time highs.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, the
country's leading fruit producer, signed its first contract to
export fruit to Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
As part of China's efforts to shift from labor-intensive to
technology-intensive production, MOFTEC has increased the
management and use of foreign trade funds and encouraged the
development of new, high-tech and high value-added products.
</P>
<P>
Starting from April 1, the country called off the export quota
on 24 products. China Import and Export Bank will increase the
credit to export complete sets of equipment.
</P>
<P>
Experiments on setting up Sino-foreign trade companies will be
carried out at port cities other than the Shenzhen Special
Economic Zone and the Pudong New Area this year, a MOFTEC official
said.
</P>
<P>
Relevant government departments are designing measures to
absorb more overseas investment and boost exports. The country
also encourages well-performing enterprises to build firms or
invest in Southeast Asia and other areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
