<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian POW Group Welcomes Comfort Women Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Two Australian "comfort women"
would be heartened by a Japanese court ruling that Japan
compensate three South Korean women forced to provide sex to
Japanese soldiers during World War II, an Australian group said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two women were among a group of up to 1,000 Australian
former prisoners of wars (POW) taking a class action against the
Japanese government over Japan's treatment of civilian POWs in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
Australian Civilian Japanese War Prisoners Reparation Action
Group, which is based in Australia's third largest city of
Brisbane, is seeking an official apology from the Japanese
government for Australian civilian POWS, as well as 14,300 U.S.
dollars for each surviving member of the group, the Australian
Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
A ruling on its case, which began in the Tokyo District Court
in 1995, is expected about July, according to the group's Chairman
Harry Rynenberg.
</P>
<P>
Rynenberg said Monday's ruling on the South Korean women was
especially pertinent to at least two Australian women who, as
civilian POWs, were raped by Japanese soldiers in WW II.
</P>
<P>
AAP, which did not provide the names of the women, said one of
the Dutch-born women now lives in Brisbane in Queensland state and
the other in Townsville, a small town in Queensland in northeast
Australia.
</P>
<P>
"This decision is particularly welcome to a few of our members
who were called Comfort Women," Rynenberg was quoted by the wire
service as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing is that the ruling puts the Japanese government
in a position where they have to pay these people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They have been steadfastly refusing that and now they have to
because this has created a precedent," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The Yamaguchi District Court in southern Japan Monday ordered
the Japanese government to pay 300,000 Japanese yen (2,270 U.S.
dollars) to each of the South Korean comfort women who were forced
to work in brothels for Japan's former Imperial Army.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Japan had refused to pay direct compensation to any
of the women, saying all claims were settled by peace treaties
that formally ended the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
