<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Improve Export Quota System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China plans to further improve
its quota system for exporters in order to increase exports of
high quality goods, according to officials with the Chinese
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic relations.
</P>
<P>
China's quota system has served as a long-term policy for the
management of exports, according to officials, noting that reform
launched in 1994 was designed to enhance the competitiveness of
local exporters.
</P>
<P>
The new policy calls for domestic exporters to win quotas
through open bidding.
</P>
<P>
China currently practices two quota systems -- active quotas on
commodities subject to government restrictions and passive quotas
for commodities subject to restrictions in foreign countries,
including textiles.
</P>
<P>
Additional quotas will be granted to exporters of brand name
goods and those exploring new markets in East Europe and Africa,
according to officials.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that the government is currently cracking down
heavily on illegal quota trading.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
