<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Vows to Keep Settlements in Occupied Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Jewish settlements in occupied
Palestinian territories will stand where they are, although they
are blamed for blocking the peace process, according to Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published by the English daily The Jerusalem
Post Tuesday, Netanyahu said his government intends to keep all
the settlements there.
</P>
<P>
"I am not delineating a map for you, but our insistence has
been on keeping all the settlements," he told the newspaper on the
eve of Israel's jubilee celebration for the 50th anniversary of
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to jeopardize the security of any one of them
(Israeli settlements)," he added.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's settlement projects, together with other hard-line
policies, have stalled the peace talks with Palestinians for over
a year. Current efforts by the United States and the European
Union to break the deadlock are making little progress due to
Israel's intransigency.
</P>
<P>
Visiting U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross continued his intensive
mediation here Monday by meeting Israeli President Ezer Weizman
and Palestinian negotiators in order to solve their dispute over
Israel's second redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who is here to prepare for the May 4 London talks
between U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Israeli
and Palestinian leaders, has so far achieved little in narrowing
the gaps.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told reporters in Jerusalem Monday night that he has
not softened his position on rejecting the U.S. plan for a 13.1
percent pullback. Israel's right-wing coalition has said it only
agreed to a redeployment of no more than 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu explained that withdrawing from over 9 percent of
West Bank would make it difficult to protect the safety of 40,000
Jewish children travelling on the West Bank's roads.
</P>
<P>
Expressing frustration over Israel's foot-dragging in the
redeployment issue, the Palestinian side has warned against dire
consequences about the failure of the latest round of American
and European mediation.
</P>
<P>
Even Weizman, an outspoken critic of Netanyahu's policies,
spoke out Monday to urge Netanyahu to be more forthcoming so as to
help advance the peace talks. Meeting twice with Netanyahu,
Weizman expressed his dissatisfaction with Netanyahu's failure to
break the peace deadlock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
