<HEADLINE> Moi Criticizes NGO's Forum on Kenya's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has criticized a forum on Kenya's economy organized by
non-governmental organizations (NGO) last weekend, saying it
ignored the existence of a constitutionally elected government
in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued Monday in Eldoret, about 320 km
northwest of Nairobi, the president said Kenya has many eminent
economists and scholars, who will comfortably discuss any facet
of the country's development needs, the Kenya Times reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He declared that the ruling Kenya African National Union
(KANU) will not support any motion arising out of the forum
which was held in the port city of Mombasa by the World Bank and
some other NGOs.
</P>
<P>
Moi stressed that his government should be the central player
in any discussions regarding the interests of Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
It is ironical that the NGOs who convened the Mombasa forum
are the same ones which are notorious for organizing strikes to
disrupt Kenya's economic activities, he added.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has no genuine reason to discuss matters in
Kenya with shady non-governmental organizations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The local Daily Nation reported Tuesday that the president's
denunciation of the two-day forum cast a shadow over its
resolutions among which is the formation of a 19-member
parliamentary committee to seek ways of salvaging the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
The forum also recommended that the number of government
ministries be reduced from 25 to 18 so as to lessen the financial
burden on the national coffers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
