<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Nations to Hold Talks on Caspian Oil Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Energy officials from Turkey,
Azerbaijan and Georgia will hold talks in Istanbul, the largest
city in Turkey, from May 5 to 6 on the Baku-Ceyhan pipeline,
Turkish Daily News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Energy Minister Cumhur Ersumer and Azerbaijani Oil
Company SOCAR Chairman Natik Aliyev will head their respective
delegations. Giorgi Canturiria, head of the Georgian Oil Company,
is to attend the talks as an observer.
</P>
<P>
The officials are expected to exchange views over the issues of
the pipeline construction aimed at exploiting the abundant
Caspian oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The planned pipeline from Azerbaijani capital of Baku to the
southern Turkish city of Ceyhan, which has 468 kilometers in
Azerbaijan, 225 kilometers in Georgia and 1,037 kilometers in
Turkey, is of great significance to the three countries' energy
industries, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by German experts and financed by the World
Bank put the total cost of the project at around 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
If completed, the pipeline is expected to have a capacity of
45 million tonness per year and the figure can be raised in the
future, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, Azerbaijani President
Geidar Aliyev and Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze met in
Turkey's Black Sea city of Trabzon Sunday. They said that the
three countries will join hands in making this huge project a
success.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, as an energy-starving country, has been playing an
active role in exploiting the Caspian oil resources to meet its
rapidly increasing energy demands and to earn foreign exchange
through the pipeline that passes through its territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
