<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funds Increased for Natural Science Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The State Natural Science Fund
Committee (SNSFC) has allocated 760 million yuan (91.6 million
U.S. dollars) to the country's natural science research, an
increase of 120 million yuan over 1997.
</P>
<P>
The committee has improved controls on funds for scientific
research and tried to help scientists involved in projects, which
cater to the country's general goals, said Zhang Cunhao, chairman
of the SNSFC, at an ongoing meeting of the Third SNSFC which
opened Monday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the committee has been providing stable financial
support for research on basic sciences, and the projects it funded
have been productive.
</P>
<P>
The committee approved 3,454 ordinary research projects in
1997, and appraised 98 key projects and 14 major projects in
scientific research. These projects were completed during the
1991-1995 period, he said.
</P>
<P>
It has set up new funds to encourage young overseas scholars to
conduct scientific research in China each year. The committee has
also made efforts to promote popular science, and expand
international exchanges and cooperation, Zhang said, adding that
SNSFC had signed agreements with 44 scientific research institutes
from 35 countries and regions by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The committee is also trying to map out a trans-century plan at
the meeting, which would include taking part in the major basic
research projects, promoting the construction of a national
innovation system, and trying to grant more funds for scientific
research efforts.
</P>
<P>
SNSFC, established in Beijing in 1986, aims to use research
funds effectively, and to coordinate and provide funds for
research in basic science and some fields of applied science in
accordance with the state policies and plans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
