<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Welcomes EU Removal of Non-Market Label </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese State Councillor Wu Yi
said today that the Chinese government welcomes the European Union
(EU)'s decision to remove China from its list of "non-market
economies".
</P>
<P>
She called the decision "sensible", and noted that it will help
ensure the development of Sino-EU trade ties remain on the proper
track.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the comments during a Xinhua News Agency interview
following her meeting with a German business delegation.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers agreed to remove the "non-market economy"
label formerly applied to both China and Russia during a Monday
council meeting in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Foreign Ministry warmly welcomed a similar EU
commission proposal tabled December 16 last year.
</P>
<P>
Economist and trade experts say the decision will help solve
problems many Chinese products have faced as a result of
anti-dumping sanctions imposed by the EU. They also note that the
EU will gradually ease controls on Chinese export to the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU is one on the list of regions which have initiated the
greatest number of anti-dumping investigations against Chinese
products, with some 70-odd related cases on file to date.
</P>
<P>
The EU has imposed quotas, export licensing and various other
controls on exports of Chinese textiles and various other light
industrial products.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the EU has removed China from the "non-market
economy" list does not mean that it regards China as a market
economy, according to Song Jian, a senior researcher with the
Chinese Academy of International Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the EU will not adopt policies applicable for market
economy countries in all anti-dumping cases involving Chinese
products and exports, said Song.
</P>
<P>
He added that that the EU should make further commitments in
order to completely solve problems related to anti-dumping cases
against Chinese goods and controls on Chinese exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Former Rebels to Undergo Training for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- About 1,400 more members of the
Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) will start a six-month
training course next month prior to their integration into the
Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP), the military said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After a thorough screening and authentication, a total of 1,361
MNLF members have qualified for training for enlisted men while 55
others qualified to the officers course, said Southern Command
Deputy Commander Col. Jessie James Catral.
</P>
<P>
Catral said the training of these MNLF members is part of a
peace agreement signed between the government and the MNLF in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, the MNLF should be disarmed and disbanded,
and some 6,000 MNLF members will be integrated into the AFP and
the police force.
</P>
<P>
The landmark agreement ended more than three decades of MNLF
separatist movement in Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
A similar number of former MNLF guerrillas have completed their
training course last year and joined the AFP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
