<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 60,000 Landmines Cleared in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Over 60,000 landmines have been
cleared in 35,000 hectares of landmine zones all over Mozambique
since the country implemented the program to accelerate de-mining
(PAD) in 1993.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed Monday by Osorio Mateus, Head of the
National Committee of De-mining, local paper Noticias reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mateus accompanied a delegation of the Non-governmental
Association of America (UNA) Monday during their visit to Moamba
landmine zone, about 70 km away from Maputo, which used to be a
base for the former anti-government organization, the Mozambique
National Resistance (Renamo).
</P>
<P>
According to Mateus, it costs about 3.5 million US Dollars a
year for the PAD to be implemented in Maputo, Gaza and Inambane
provinces with the support of the Mozambican government and the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that the PAD will soon be carried out in
areas along the Maputo-Komatipoorti (South Africa) high pressure
transmission line. The project has gained a three-million-Dollar
assistance from a French bank.
</P>
<P>
The results of the U.S. delegation's visit will be announced
at a special meeting by the U.S. State Department on May 20 to
22.
</P>
<P>
About two million landmines had been planted around Mozambique
during its 16-year-long civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
