<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seeks Effective Therapy for Liver Cancer Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese doctors have found an
effective measure to deal with the later stages of liver cancer
with a patented multi-needle, cold-therapy apparatus.
</P>
<P>
Investigation indicates that, among 53 liver cancer patients
who had received the cold therapy in Shiyan City in central
China's Hubei Province, more than 40 percent survived two years
and five people had survived for five years.
</P>
<P>
In usual cases, patients in the medium or later stages of liver
cancer only survive three to six months. Liver cancer is being
regarded in the medical field as the "king of cancers" because of
the high death rate.
</P>
<P>
The multi-needle cold therapy apparatus, developed at the
central hospital of Dongfeng Motor Vehicle Company, passed
state-level appraisal earlier this week in Shiyan City.
</P>
<P>
Different from other countries' shallow-position cold therapy,
the China-made apparatus can go deeper.
</P>
<P>
The apparatus inserts several specially-made needles into the
liver cancer lump from different directions and uses low
temperatures to kill cancer cells on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
The cancer cells can be killed in 20 degrees below zero
centigrade. The cold therapy could effectively control the
development of liver cancer cells. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Company to Launch Satellites From Australia: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard said Tuesday that his government had signed an agreement
with the U.S.-based Kistler Aerospace Corp to launch satellites
from Australia's rocket-launching town of Woomera.
</P>
<P>
The launching facilities at Woomera will be upgraded by the
company Tony O'Leary, a spokesman for the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the agreement paves the way for an initial
investment of 32 million U.S. dollars from Kistler in the project,
under which tests are expected to begin by the end of this year
with the first commercial launch possibly in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The project would ultimately generate up to 1.88 billion U.S.
dollars over the next 12 years with the possible launch of one 65
million U.S. dollar reusable satellite-bearing rocket "every two
weeks," the prime minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Germany and some other countries used to have rockets
launched at Woomera in the past decades, O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
"It is estimated that over 1,000 communication satellites will
be launched around the world over the next 10 years and this
project helps vision Australia alongside the United States, Russia
and China as a top country in space and communications
technology," Howard said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
