<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Welcomes EU Removal of Non-Market Label </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese State Councillor Wu Yi
said today that the Chinese government welcomes the European Union
(EU)'s decision to remove China from its list of "non-market
economies".
</P>
<P>
She called the decision "sensible", and noted that it will help
ensure that the development of Sino-EU trade ties remain on the
right track.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the comments in response to questions by a Xinhua News
Agency correspondent following her meeting with a German business
delegation.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers agreed to remove the "non-market economy"
label formerly applied to both China and Russia during a Monday
council meeting in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, Shi
Guangsheng, also expressed welcome to the decision, saying
that it is of great importance to China because it makes
a great difference in conducting anti-dumping investigations.
</P>
<P>
For a non-market economy country, if the anti-dumping tax is
levied on one of its products, all other products of the same
category will be punished likewise, Shi explained.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he added, the price of the products of a
non-market economy country will be calculated according to that of
a surrogate country instead of its domestic price.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the Chinese Foreign Ministry Zhu Bangzao also
extended a welcome to the EU decision here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Economist and trade experts here agree that the decision will
not only help solve problems many Chinese products have
encountered as a result of anti-dumping investigations conducted
by the EU. They also note that this will lead EU to gradually
lifting controls on Chinese exports to the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU is one on the list of regions which have initiated the
greatest number of anti-dumping investigations against Chinese
products, with some 70-odd related cases on file to date.
</P>
<P>
The EU has imposed quotas, export licensing and various other
controls on exports of Chinese textiles, silk products and various
other light industrial goods.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the EU has removed China from the "non-market
economy" list does not mean that it regards China as a market
economy, according to Song Jian, a senior researcher with the
Chinese Academy of International Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the EU will not adopt policies applicable for market
economy countries in all anti-dumping cases involving Chinese
products and exports, said Song.
</P>
<P>
He added that that the EU should make further commitments in
order to completely solve problems related to anti-dumping cases
against Chinese goods and controls on Chinese exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Prepared to Receive Prisoners Released by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordan is prepared to receive the
13 Jordanian prisoners released Monday by the Kuwaiti authorities,
semi-official Jordan Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent, has issued orders for all
necessary preparations to receive as soon as possible the
Jordanians who were jailed by Kuwait for allegedly collaborating
with Iraq during the Gulf War in 1991, Jordan's acting Foreign
Minister Sami Gammo said Monday during an exclusive interview with
the paper.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to bring them home at any time. We are only
waiting for the formalities to be concluded, and that might take
some time," said Gammo.
</P>
<P>
It was announced on Monday night that Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber
Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah has issued an amnesty to release the 13
Jordanians held since 1991 in the latest gesture of reconciliation
with Jordan which supported Iraq during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gammo expressed Jordan's gratitude to the Kuwaiti
emir for granting the amnesty, saying that Jordan hopes the
"brotherly relations" between the two countries will develop
further.
</P>
<P>
Monday's release is the result of continued efforts by the
Jordanian leadership to secure the release of all the Jordanians
jailed by Kuwait on charges of "collaborating" with Iraq, whose
number is estimated at around 60, the paper quoted anonymous
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
On February 25, 1997, Kuwait released 10 Jordanians under
another amnesty by the Kuwaiti emir.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-Kuwaiti relations were strained following the
Gulf War when Jordan sided with Iraq, which occupied Kuwait for
seven months before the allied forces drove the Iraqi troops out
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The emirate downgraded its diplomatic representation in Amman
to the level of charge d'affaires. But bilateral ties have been
improving since last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
