<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak-Netanyahu Talks End, No Progress Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
apparently failed to persuade visiting Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to offer compromise in Mideast peace process
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders held a two-hour-and-half meeting at the Salem
Palace here, an unusual venue of Mubarak's talks with foreign
leaders, shunning any reporters.
</P>
<P>
No press conferences or briefings were given by either leaders
or any officials. This was interpreted as an indication of a very
tough talk.
</P>
<P>
This has also broken up the custom pursued during Netanyahu's
previous visits that Netanyahu and Mubarak talked to reporters
after their meetings no matter how the talks went.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu left here immediately after the meeting, ending his
hours' visit, the fourth of the kind he paid since taking office
about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was believed to have urged Netanyahu to make compromise
in the scope of redeployment from the West Bank before the London
Israeli-Palestinian peace meeting and issued his warning of the
dangerous situation facing the region if the peace process
collapses.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Netanyahu summit preceded the four-way London talks
on May 4 to be co-hosted by British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who will hold separate
meetings with Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace making has been frozen after
Israel started a Jewish settlement on Arab East Jerusalem in March
1997 and deteriorated over the long-delayed Israeli redeployment
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has refused to accept any proposal
calling for more than 9 percent troop pullback in the West
Bank. But some reports said Netanyahu is considering an 11 percent
pullback in exchange for Palestinians' promise to intensify fight
against terrorism and enter the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross has met twice in the past
three days with Netanyahu to persuade him to accept a proposal for
a 13.1 percent redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
As a compromise, the PNA has already endorsed the proposal and
is demanding the U.S. pressure Israel to accept the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
