<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Issue Bonds for Easing Liquidity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government plans to
issue bonds worth 500 billion baht (13.5 billion U.S. dollars) in
a bid to ease the liquidity crunch and bring down interest rates.
</P>
<P>
An official of Thailand's central bank disclosed Tuesday that
the measures will be submitted to the cabinet later in the day for
approval.
</P>
<P>
If the cabinet approves the measures, the Financial Ministry
will announce further details, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has proposed that the funds raised in the
local bond offering be allocated to its financial institutions
development fund, commonly known as the rescue fund, which has
provided large loans to debt-ridden banks and finance companies.
</P>
<P>
The decision to issue long-term local bonds is part of a
four-point plan to lower interest rates by easing the pressure on
the domestic short-term money market, said the official, who
refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
Financial authorities involved in the restructuring and
recapitalization of troubled financial institutions have come
under increasing political pressure to bring down the high lending
rates punishing Thailand's struggling private sector.
</P>
<P>
The three other measures to soften interest rates involve
commercial banks raising 90 billion baht (2.4 billion dollars) in
fresh capital, the government tapping foreign money markets to
boost local liquidity, and keeping under control competition for
deposits among local banks.
</P>
<P>
The central bank believed that interest rates would be brought
down if these measures were implemented.
</P>
<P>
For the measures to work effectively, however, the baht must be
stable and inflation must remain at an appropriate level, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The baht has been stable since mid-March around 39 to 40 baht
to the dollar, down about 34 percent since the central bank
floated the currency last July.
</P>
<P>
But inflation is on the rise, with the consumer price index
rising 9.5 percent year-on-year in March, compared with 8.9
percent in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
