<HEADLINE> Rwanda's Ex-PM to Be on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Former Rwandan Prime Minister
Jean Kambanda will be on initial trial at the International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) Friday, four days before U.N.
chief Kofi Annan's scheduled visit to the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The former Rwandan prime minister is charged with conspiracy
and direct and public incitement to commit genocide as well as
crimes against humanity, according to a news release issued
Tuesday by the ICTR based in northern Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The 42-year-old man is the highest ranking Rwandan
ex-political leader indicted for genocide and detained by the
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda was prime minister of Rwanda from 8 April 1994 until
mid July 1994 when he left the tiny central African state. He was
arrested in July last year in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal has conducted only four trials and no verdict has
been made so far. Twenty-five out of a total of 35 indicted by
the U.N now are detained by the tribunal in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal was often criticized for its snail-paced progress
towards visible justice for more than 500,000 Tutsis and moderate
Hutus killed in the 1994 Rwanda genocide.
</P>
<P>
However, Annan's May 5 visit "is an indication of the
consistent support the secretary-general has provided to the
Tribunal since he took office in early 1997," said the ICTR.
</P>
</TEXT>
