<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Postal Unions Demand Withdrawal Of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's postal unions have
demanded the withdrawal of the police and the Army from the
Central Mail Exchange (CME) if the government wanted the postal
services to return to normal, informed sources here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The military and police were moved in last Friday night after
government promulgated Emergency regulations to declare the Postal
and Telecommunication Service an "Essential Service" following a
44-day strike by postal unions demanding overtime payments.
</P>
<P>
Twelve Union leaders, who were arrested and later released,
were brought Monday before the Colombo Chief Magistrate A.L.M
Saheed who warned them not to cause a breach of the peace and
discharged them.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of the Union of Posts and Telecom Officers
N.P. Hettiarachchi was quoted by the sources as saying that the
overtime boycott of the 5000 members of his union will continue
until their demands are met in full despite the postal service
being declared an Essential Service.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, there is a backlog of twenty
containers of sea mail, 25,000 bags of air mail, 3 million
registered letters and 7.5 million ordinary letters in the CME.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Posts Mangala Samaraweera Monday expressed
confidence that the backlog will be cleared by Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
