<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Favors Political Solution to Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadezhda
Mikhailova said trade sanctions on Yugoslavia should be the last
resort after all precautious diplomatic means are exhausted.
</P>
<P>
In an interview carried by the Bulgarian newspaper Capital on
Monday, Mikhailova called possible sanctions against Belgrade for
its handling of the Kosovo crisis an "extreme alternative."
</P>
<P>
The international community, she said, should be more cautious
this time than imposing sanctions years ago during the Bosnia war.
</P>
<P>
Previous sanctions were "disastrous" also to other countries in
the region, resulting in their heavy direct economic losses and a
sharp rise of criminal activities in economic life, she said.
</P>
<P>
However, in a related development Monday, the European Union
(EU) threatened to step up sanctions to press Yugoslavia into
talks with ethnic Albanians in its autonomous province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
On Mikhailova part, she had sent a letter to foreign ministers
of the six nations making up the Contact Group on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Mikhailova said, she proposed the two
conflicting parties in Kosovo state their stands and possible
compromises in written form, and then go into talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
