<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Adopts Japan-U.S. Defense Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government adopted
Tuesday two bills and a draft revision of a bilateral agreement
for implementing updated Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The two bills will be submitted to the Diet, or parliament,
within the day at the earliest, Japanese government officials were
quoted as saying by a Kyodo News report.
</P>
<P>
The draft revision was signed Tuesday morning by Japanese
Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi and visiting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The proposed measures expand the scope of bilateral security
from the defense of Japanese territory to providing support for
the U.S. military in vaguely defined "areas surrounding Japan that
have an important influence on Japan's peace and security."
</P>
<P>
One bill allows Japan's Self-Defense Forces (SDF) to provide
rear support in supplies and services to U.S. forces, assist in
the search and rescue of injured U.S. military personnel, and
inspect ships of other nations on the high seas to ensure the
enforcement of economic sanctions approved by the United Nations
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Another bill would revise the SDF Law in line with the new
guidelines so as to allow Japanese warships and ship-borne
helicopters to evacuate Japanese nationals overseas.
</P>
<P>
The draft proposal would revise the Japan-U.S. Acquisition and
Cross-Servicing Agreement to match the new guidelines, as the
current agreement is effective only in peacetime.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the United States agreed last September on the
revised version of the 1978 bilateral defense cooperation
guidelines. The new version calls for Japan to provide more active
support to the U.S. military in the event of emergencies in "areas
surrounding Japan." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
