<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Arrives in Cairo for Talks With Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Amid intensive diplomatic efforts
to unlock the Mideast peace logjam, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu arrived here Tuesday morning on a lightning
visit to Egypt for talks with President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is expected to warn the Israeli leader on the dangerous
situation facing the region if the peace process collapses.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders entered meeting Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is on his fourth visit to Egypt since taking office
about two years ago. Egyptian-Israeli ties have been further
strained since then.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace making has been frozen after
Israel started a Jewish settlement on Arab East Jerusalem in March
1997 and deteriorated over the long-delayed Israeli redeployment
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Israeli government Danny Naveh Monday
paid a short visit to Egypt during which he discussed with
Mubarak's political advisor Ossama al-Baz arrangements for
Netanyahu's visit to Cairo and issues that will be tabled during
the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
Naveh told reporters that the arrangements for Israel's troops
redeployment is "unnegotiable," which has to be decided according
to its security need.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the Israeli government has not indicated any
willingness to accept any proposal calling for more than 9
percent troop pullback in the West Bank. But some reports said
Netanyahu is considering an 11 percent pullback in exchange for
PNA's promise to increase fight against terrorism and enter the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross has met twice in the past
three days with Netanyahu to persuade him to accept a proposal for
a 13.1 percent redeployment in the West Bank so to break the
year-old deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
As a compromise, the PNA has already endorsed the proposal and
is demanding the U.S. pressure Israel to accept the plan.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, in an interview with the American T.V. network NBC
Monday, said he and Netanyahu will try their utmost to solve the
problems in the region during their talks Tuesday. He also renewed
warning against the explosion of terrorism if peace fails.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Netanyahu summit preceded the four-way London talks
on May 4 to be co-hosted by British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who will hold separate
meetings with Netanyahu and Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AmCham Lobbies for Permanent MFN Status for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The American commerce
community in China began Monday its annual lobbying in the United
States for China's permanent most favored nation(MFN) trade status
with a hope for weaker opposition from Congress.
</P>
<P>
A 30-member delegation from the Beijing-based American
Chamber (AmCham) of Commerce in China arrived here Sunday and
called a press conference to air its point of view in favor of
stronger trade ties with China the next day.
</P>
<P>
Vaughn A. Koshkarian, head of the delegation and also
vice president of Ford Motor Company, said that he and his
entourages share the belief that the United States should
"de-politicize and normalize trade with China by extending MFN
status on a permanent, unconditional basis and by removing all
unilateral commercial sanctions against China."
</P>
<P>
The MFN status for China has become a thorny issue over which
Congress debates once a year. The United States has given the
status to 227 countries in the world and only four nations
including China are denied the normal trade treatment.
</P>
<P>
Although President Bill Clinton has delinked the human rights
issue with trade regarding China, the annual congressional debate
over China's MFN has actually provided platform for attacking
Beijing's overall policy.
</P>
<P>
"The annual debate over China's MFN status undermines U.S.
commercial interests in China and significantly strains the
U.S.-China relations," Amcham said in a policy statement.
</P>
<P>
The delegation represents some 600 American companies in
China. It expressed the fears that "withdrawal or conditioning of
MFN would be a potentially destabilizing move in a region already
rocked by financial and trade uncertainties."
</P>
<P>
The delegation will be divided into six working groups and
plans to meet 250 congressmen, both proponents and opponents to
China's MFN, this week.
</P>
<P>
John L. Holden, Chairman &AMP; General Manager of Carcill
Investments (China) LTD., expressed the belief that the mood in
the House this year would be more "positive" because of the
changes in, and better understanding, of China by many
Congressional members who visited China last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, more than 100 Senators and House representatives
visited China.
</P>
<P>
"When they returned home none of them said the trip was not
positive," said Rudolph A. Schlais, president of General Motors
China Operations.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton is obliged to recommend to Congress by June 3
that China's MFN be or not be renewed. The House of
Representatives has 30 days to determine.
</P>
<P>
James W. Jarrett, president of Intel China, shared the belief
that the Administration is in favor of permanent MFN for China.
</P>
<P>
The issue is now linked to China's accession to the World Trade
Organization (WTO), over which the United States and China are
continuing their difficult negotiations.
</P>
<P>
China wants to be treated as a developing country, but the
United States and some other industrialized countries are pushing
for further opening of the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
If China can become a WTO member, its MFN status will no longer
make sense. However, no one can predict when the process will be
over.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will visit China in late June. It is believed that
China's WTO membership will be high on the agenda of his summit
with Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that President Clinton's visit to China will
be very successful," said Vaughn, who declined to specify his
expectations from the president's trip.
</P>
<P>
The delegation voiced its hope that China will further "level
the playing field for American exports" so as to balance the
growing trade deficit, and to increase transparency and enhance
the rule of law to minimize risks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
