<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Welcomes Return of 'Golden Buddha' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- One after another, Tibetan
Buddhists went to a lamasery in the suburbs of Lhasa to worship a
recently returned 'Golden Buddha,' according to today's People's
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The country's leading newspaper reported that the
1,200-year-old Buddha, made of alloy, was enshrined in the Netang
Zholma Lhakham Lamasery. On April 9, 1993, it was stolen by two
thieves in a minivan, then sold to smugglers in the southwestern
city of Chengdu for 300,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Three years later, the Lhasa Customs received a clue that the
Buddha had arrived in the United States and would be sold for
eight million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the Lhasa Customs, the U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation took possession of the relic. However, the
U.S. agency required China to provide pictures or videos to prove
that Tibet is the owner.
</P>
<P>
This presented a problem for the Chinese since there was no
such picture or video, the paper reported. Though computer systems
have been installed in museums and temples in inland areas, the
management of cultural relics in most lamaseries in snow-covered
Tibet remains backward.
</P>
<P>
Tibet Customs finally located a photograph of the Buddha taken
by a foreigner on his Tibetan tour.
</P>
<P>
The United States accepted the evidence and agreed to return
the Buddha.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony held in Hong Kong in November, Ngawang Chagba, a
monk in the lamasery, paid his respects to the returned Buddha
with tears in his eyes, then carefully wrapped the relic with his
yellow kasaya.
</P>
<P>
When told the news, Tibetan people in Lhasa crowded along the
streets near the airport to welcome the Buddha back home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
