<HEADLINE> Modern Laboratory Established in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A modern laboratory worth of
600 million Uganda Shillings (some 500,000 U.S. Dollars) for
analysing water quality has been established in Entebbe, central
Uganda, local newspaper The New Vision reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The laboratory which began operation last Friday was
constructed with the assistance of Danish International
Development Agency (DANIDA).
</P>
<P>
The laboratory is part of the water resources assessment
project of directorate of water development. It is the first of
its kind of international standard in east and central Africa.
</P>
<P>
Only 40 percent of Ugandans have access to safe drinking
water, said Gerald Sendaula, Minister of Water Resources at the
opening ceremony of the lab on last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government has obligation to provide the Ugandan
people with safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
The minister asked local people to report to the authorities
concerned about suspected water with the samples.
</P>
<P>
Enoch Drabidu, the project coordinator, said water in Uganda
sometimes bear poisonous substances and germs that cause illness.
</P>
<P>
A recent report said some people are engaged in illegal
fishing operation with poisonous substances.
</P>
<P>
During the last rainy season, there are outbreaks of malaria
and cholera in the African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
