<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market to Play Greater Role in Cotton Pricing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China will allow the market to
play a greater role in cotton pricing and earlier this month
announced the abandonment of the official pricing system for the
commodity.
</P>
<P>
The government has introduced a new policy based on indirect
control and guideline prices for cotton.
</P>
<P>
The reform goals center on reducing stockpiles of domestic
cotton resulting from rapid increases in the cotton supply and
decreases in demand due to high prices, according to today's
Economic Daily.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that China witnessed rapidly increasing
cotton stockpiles and marketing cooperatives across the nation,
with March levels standing at 700 million kg, up 38 percent on the
previous year's period. However, current cotton reserves are close
to the required consumption volume for textile production over a
six month period.
</P>
<P>
Supply and marketing cooperatives sustained losses totalling
one billion yuan in 1997 due to excessive cotton stockpiles,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
China has also decided to lower the state purchase price for
cotton in bid to solve problems resulting from supply exceeding
demand.
</P>
<P>
State purchase prices for cotton stood at 700 yuan per 50 kg in
1997, and are expected to hover around 650 yuan per 50 kg this
year..
</P>
<P>
Total market demand of cotton will hit 3.25 billion kg by the
year 2000 when considering the impact of a reduced textile
production capacity, the effects of financial turmoil in Southeast
Asia on textile exports, and increased cotton imports.
</P>
<P>
More than 43 million rural Chinese households, or 150 million
people, depend on cotton production. This year's price cuts will
not affect the income levels of cotton growers since China has
slashed prices for chemical fertilizers by 20 percent and the per
unit cotton yield has increased as a result of the extensive
application of advanced agro-techniques.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show the country produced 4.3 billion kg of
cotton in 1997, up 100 million kg on the previous year. The 1997
state purchase volume for cotton stood at 3.07 billion
kg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0221 </DOCNO>
