<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Emir Amnesties 13 Jordanian Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber
Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah has issued an amnesty to release 13 Jordanian
prisoners held since 1991 in Kuwait Central Prison in the latest
gesture of reconciliation with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Kuwaiti Interior Minister Sheikh Mohammad
Khaled Al-Hamad Al-Sabah on Monday night, Kuwait News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the Kuwaiti emir issued amnesty since
1997 to release Jordanians serving prison terms in Kuwait for
various offenses. Kuwait released 10 Jordanians in February 1997
under another amnesty of the emir.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners who have been amnestied were convicted by the
State Security Court in 1991 following the Gulf War, during which
Jordan supported Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti interior minister said his ministry is also
coordinating with the Foreign Ministry to deport 25 Jordanians who
have been arrested by the Deportation Administration and were found
using a group travel document.
</P>
<P>
The 25 Jordanians will be repatriated after the Foreign
Ministry contacts the Jordanian authorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
The decision of amnesty was made on the eve of a travel to
Kuwait arranged by the International Committee of the Red Cross of
26 Jordanian families on May 4 for a three-day stay to visit their
relatives jailed in the Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
This will be the fourth visit by these relatives since
1995. Fifty-one Jordanians visited their families last year,
according to the interior minister.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kuwait and Jordan were strained following the
Gulf War in 1991 when Jordan sided with Iraq, which occupied
Kuwait for seven months before the allied forces drove the
Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral ties have been improving since last year within the
framework of a reconciliatory process by the Kuwaiti authorities
with its "former enemy states."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait resumed air flights with Jordan last year after a
seven-year suspension following the Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
