<HEADLINE> Six Companies Intend to Buy Shares of Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Six foreign companies have
tendered their bid to buy a stake in the Uganda Airlines,
the Privatisation Unit announced at a Monday morning
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Privatisation Unit Director Michael Opagi said the six bidders
are British Airways, Kenya Airways, Alliance Air, Sabena, Air
Mauritius and Aero Zambia/Interair. The result will be announced
at the end of April.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that international investment bankers
from Hong Kong and Shanghai Bank of Commerce will, through its
Kampala affiliate, the Equator Bank, be advising on the airlines'
privatisation.
</P>
<P>
According to the invitation to prospective investors, the
bidders are expected to have safe and efficient air transport and
develop Entebbe Airport as a regional air transport hub. Either
in consortium or as single entities, the bidders must have an
internationally renown air transport operator and have passenger
and cargo services on intercontinental routes.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the companies involved must have a worldwide
sales network, a satisfactory safety record and first class
computer reservation system.
</P>
<P>
In mid-March, the Ugandan government invited pre-qualification
bids from investors interested in buying a significant portion of
the national carrier. It will sell the remaining shares to the
public through the Uganda Stock Exchange. 
</P>
