<HEADLINE> S'pore Wants to Join Berne Convention to Protect IP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore said on Tuesday that
it is ready to accede to the Berne Convention for the Protection
of Literary and Artistic Works, adding that it is in its "national
interest" to do so.
</P>
<P>
"We will do so shortly as soon as the necessary Instrument of
Accession is processed in accordance with WIPO (World Intellectual
Property Organization) procedures," Minister for Law and Foreign
Affairs S. Jayakumar told a Seminar on the Internet and the
Protection of Intellectual Property Rights.
</P>
<P>
He said Singapore is committed to a policy of giving proper
protection to intellectual property rights, including patents,
trade marks, industrial design and copyright.
</P>
<P>
"It is in our national interest to do so. We will strengthen
our linkage with WIPO and other world bodies to signal our
resolve," he added.
 He also said the Singapore Government is well aware of the
potential of the Internet for conducting business activities and
has just put in place a framework for supporting Electronic
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Within this framework, the government is looking at legislation
that will, among other things, protect intellectual property
rights on the Internet and provide legal recourse in the case of
infringement of such rights, Jayakumar said.
</P>
<P>
He said an Inter-Ministry Committee, chaired by the Register of
Trade Marks and Patents, was formed earlier this month to examine
these and other copyright issues in relation to electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
The committee will complete its work by the end of this year,
and will recommend further changes to Singapore's copyright
legislation, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
