<HEADLINE> Kenya Determined to Revamp Ailing Agriculture: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Agriculture Minister
Musalia Mudavadi said that the government is determined to revamp
agriculture through an Agricultural Sector Investment Program
(ASIP).
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Tuesday quoted Mudavadi as saying that the
sub-sector has recorded decreased output in the fields of coffee,
cereal, diary, cotton, pyrethrum and sugar-cane in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He told an ASIP preparation workshop held here last week that
the ASIP will alter the development path of Kenya's agricultural
sector in terms of production structure.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the program is to empower and not to
control the farmers in the private sector, Mudavadi said.
</P>
<P>
"We also recognize the wider liberalization thrust which is
aimed at enabling greater participation of the private sector in
direct production, with the government playing a more
facilitative role," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to participants to the workshop, the first phase of
ASIP will focus on improved service delivery by the Ministry of
Agriculture and the ministry will also plan to provide linkages
and harmonization of activities undertaken by players in the
sector under the program.
</P>
<P>
On another occasion, the minister said the government is
reviewing agricultural policy with a primary objective of
achieving an effective recovery in food production.
</P>
<P>
The review will try to rationalize the ministry's operations
to make them compatible with changing farmers' needs, he said.
</P>
<P>
The review will lay emphasis on private sectors' participation
through privatization and commercialization of some major
services previously offered by the government, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
