<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Projects Incur Heavy Debt in Central China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Two key projects established in
central China's Henan Province at a cost of over 3.3 billion yuan
have incurred heavy debts totaling 6.5 billion yuan over the past
four years.
</P>
<P>
The Zhongyuan Pharmaceutical Plant, the largest medical project
introduced in China in 1986-1995, was established at a cost of
1.33 billion yuan. The plant has a designed annual production
capacity of 5,000 tons of vitamin C., according to today's
"People's Daily," the leading national newspaper.
</P>
<P>
However, serious problems with imported equipment prevented
the plant from fulfilling production plan and the operation was
forced to close after amassing a debt of over three billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Zhongzhou Aluminium Plant, built in 1993 at a cost of 1.98
billion yuan, has incurred 3.5 billion yuan in debt resulting from
overeager efforts to become a large-scale operation.
</P>
<P>
The two cases have sent shock waves through party and government
officials in Henan, with some attributing the losses to blind
investments and the rash importation of equipment, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
A commentary in the paper today urged people to draw lessons
from the status of the two projects.
</P>
<P>
The ability of policy-makers to adapt to a market-oriented
economy constitutes the most important element in economic
development in the absence of reform to China's existing
investment system, according to the commentary.
</P>
<P>
The commentary pointed out that most prominent waste in
economic construction centers erroneous investment decisions and
redundant project construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
