<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Accuse Rivals of Opposing Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban
militia have accused the rival Northern Alliance of opposing peace
in the first round of talks between the two sides currently being
held in Islamabad, said reports monitored here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban-run Radio Shariat said the alliance representatives
backed down from their earlier stand and were now opposed to the
formation of the Ulema Commission to resolve the country's
protracted conflict.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance was therefore opposed to a peaceful
solution to the Afghan conflict, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
"The opposition delegation are not ready to accept the Ulema
Commission," said the radio, the mouthpiece of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which started on Sunday, were suspended Monday to
enable both delegations to consult with their top leaders over the
issue of who should be qualified to sit on the proposed
commission.
</P>
<P>
"It is now clear that the opposition do not want peace because
they are advancing such terms which nobody had mentioned in the
past," the radio said. 
</P>
