<HEADLINE> Chinese State Councillor Meets with President of German Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese State Councillor Wu Yi
said that China will gradually open its service trade sector in
meeting here today with Bernd Bothe, president of Germany's Metro
A.G.
</P>
<P>
Wu attributed China's achievements in reform and opening-up to
the Chinese government developing the economy in line with the
country's national conditions and adopting methods of proceeding
on a step-by-step basis.
</P>
<P>
China is shifting from a planned economy to a market economy,
Wu said, adding that China has carried out experimental retail
methods by allowing one or two retail joint ventures to be
established in six coastal cities and five special economic zones
of China.
</P>
<P>
During the experimental period, China will accumulate
experience, train professionals, tighten supervision and
management and formulate relevant law and regulations, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
China will check on and rectify joint ventures involving retail
trade which have been set up without Chinese government approval,
Wu added.
</P>
<P>
Bothe briefed Wu on the operation of Metro, and said his group
will participate actively in China's retail trade.
</P>
<P>
Metro is the second largest sales company in the world. It has
more than 3,000 branches in 19 countries and regions such as
Germany, Denmark, France and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
