<HEADLINE> Israel's Unemployment Rate Hits New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel's unemployment rate
continued to climb this year and reached 8.3 percent in February,
its highest level since the end of 1993, the English daily The
Jerusalem Post reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli Central Bureau of Statistic as
saying that the rise in the jobless rate has brought the
number of people out of work to more than 180,000.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted recently found that 72 percent of the
unemployed believe that the government is not doing enough to
solve the unemployment problem, and 86 percent do not believe
they will find jobs via the employment bureau.
</P>
<P>
In response to the rising unemployment rate, Israeli Finance
Minister Yaakov Neeman is going to introduce a job-generating
program soon.
</P>
<P>
The program will urge the government to impose hefty fines on
employers who take on illegal foreign workers. Neeman estimated
this week that the number of foreign workers without valid permits
in Israel is now over 160,000.
</P>
<P>
The program will call for increasing state and private
spending on infrastructure, and reforming the tax system and the
capital market.
</P>
<P>
It will also ask the government to provide aid to a variety of
unemployment black spots in the country, including examining
development towns on a factory-by-factory basis to see where new
jobs can be created. Additionally, the government would see how to
provide appropriate academic and vocational training courses.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
is already fully behind the program which Neeman will present
at next week's cabinet meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Promise More Loans to Sustain Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Two leading Chinese banks have
pledged to grant more loans to ensure the planned economic growth
of 8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC) plans to
grant 200 billion yuan (24 billion U.S. dollars) of new loans this
year, compared to 193 billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
ICBC will increase loans in railway, highway,
telecommunications, urban construction and key industries by about
10 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank will issue 25 billion yuan of loans especially for
the construction of inexpensive houses and mortgages for home
buyers to support government housing reform.
</P>
<P>
While backing will continue to be given to 500 key state-owned
enterprises, the bank will also pay attention to support small-
and medium-size enterprises and foreign-funded businesses.
</P>
<P>
Despite an increase in loans, the bank will not relax loan
conditions to avoid bad loans, an ICBC spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
China Construction Bank has also announced plans to grant 31
billion yuan in loans for fixed-asset development in
infrastructure and technical upgrading of existing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The bank also plans to issue 25 billion yuan in loans for
housing construction and 15 billion yuan of loans for individual
home buyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
