<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, April 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Amid intensive diplomatic efforts to unlock the
Mideast peace logjam, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
arrived here Tuesday on a lightning visit to Egypt for talks with
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is expected to warn the Israeli leader on the dangerous
situation facing the region if the peace process collapses.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is on his fourth visit to Egypt since taking office
about two years ago. Egyptian-Israeli ties have been further
strained since then. (Egypt-Netanyahu Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- The Japanese government Tuesday adopted two bills and
a draft revision of a bilateral agreement for implementing updated
Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The two bills will be submitted to the Diet, or parliament,
within the day at the earliest, Japanese government officials were
quoted as saying by a Kyodo News report.
</P>
<P>
The proposed measures expand the scope of bilateral security
from the defense of Japanese territory to providing support for
the U.S. military in vaguely defined "areas surrounding Japan that
have an important influence on Japan's peace and security," said
the report. (Japan-US-Defense Guidelines)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Security Council of the United Nations
Monday reached no consensus on lifting sanctions against Iraq
after day-long consultations, thus the U.N. sanctions against Iraq
will remain.
</P>
<P>
Before the consultations, the Security Council was briefed by
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and UNSCOM on their
latest reports on the inspections of Iraq weapons in the past six
months.
</P>
<P>
The IAEA said Iraq has met its demands by having destroyed all
its nuclear weapons, and the UNSCOM said there was no virtual
progress made by Iraq in the areas of chemical, biological weapons
and ballistic misslies, especially in the area of biological
weapons. (UN-Iraq-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Three ethnic Albanians were killed and four injured
Monday in a fresh clash between Yugoslav border guards and ethnic
Albanians in the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Two policemen were also injured when ethnic Albanians attacked
a Yugoslav police office in Kosovo at 0045 a.m. Monday, Yugoslav
military sources said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav news agency said Yugoslav border guards exchanged fire
with ethnic Albanians in the Albanian border area west of Dechani,
Kosovo, at 0300 a.m. The police seized a large amount of arms and
military equipment, the sources said. (Kosovo-Clashes) 
</P>
