<HEADLINE> S. African Blacks Urged to Vote As One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A senior South African
official has appealed to black people in the country to unite and
vote as one during next year's elections and continue to fight
for economic freedom.
</P>
<P>
"There is still a bigger job for us as black people to come
together to fight the economic struggle," Correctional Services
Minister Sipo Mzimela said at Freedom Day celebrations here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There are many people who do not want to see us united. They
fear that if we are one, nothing will ever defeat us. By the time
we vote next year, we must vote as one," local press reports
Tuesday quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The national celebrations of Freedom Day were held throughout
South Africa Monday to mark the first all-race elections in the
country in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mathole Motshekga, Premier of Gauteng Province, and 3,000
people participated in the celebrations in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Motshekga told the crowd that Freedom Day means people should
be free from crime. "Now is the time to reclaim our streets from
the criminals," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The criminals' days are numbered. Our battle plans to crush
criminals are ready," Motshekga said.
</P>
<P>
Crime in Gauteng Province where the commercial hub of
Johannesburg and the administrative capital of Pretoria are
situated, is generally believed to be the most serious social
problem in the province. 
</P>
