<HEADLINE> Philippines' Poll Body Junks Disqualification Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Commission on
Elections (Comelec) on Tuesday dismissed a petition seeking to
disqualify presidential candidate Alfredo Lim on the grounds that
he is not a natural-born Filipino citizen.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution, the poll body junked the petition filed by
lawyer Andresito Fornier for lack of jurisdiction over the
question of Lim's citizenship.
</P>
<P>
The Comelec said it was not the proper authority to hear the
case and only the Supreme Court can act on such cases.
</P>
<P>
Fornier, a long-time foe of Lim, filed early this month the
petition to disqualify Lim from running in the May 11 elections on
the grounds that the former Manila mayor was not a natural-born
Filipino citizen because his parents were "Chinese mestizos."
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, only natural-born Filipinos may seek
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
But according to copies of birth certificates Lim submitted to
the Comelec, Lim, the standard-bearer of the Liberal Party, is a
"Filipino."
</P>
<P>
Lim, one of the front runners in the presidential race, has
accused National Security Adviser Jose Almonte of the ruling
Lakas-NUCD Party of being behind the moves to question his
citizenship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
