<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Continues to Be China's Top Priority: President (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin,
receiving the Agricola Medal from the U.N. Food and Agricultural
Organization (FAO), pledged here today that China will
unswervingly give top priority to agriculture in the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony held at the Great Hall of the People, UNFAO
Director-General Jacques Diouf presented Jiang the medal, which
specially honors those heads of state who have made outstanding
contributions to the world's agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
"The Agricola Medal conferred on me by the UNFAO is not only an
honor for myself, but more importantly, a full recognition of the
efforts made by the Chinese Government and people in resolving the
question of food and agriculture," said the president while
addressing the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people once suffered grievously from hunger and
poverty, and now China has grown into a big food producer and
consumer country, and has scored "remarkable achievements" in
energetically expanding food and agricultural production, Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, in 1997, China's grain output reached 492.5
billion kg., and the grain reserves hit a historic high. China's
grain, meat, aquatic products and fruits have either reached or
exceeded the world's average in per capita output.
</P>
<P>
"China has, by relying on its own efforts, supported 1.2
billion people on limited arable land, thus making an important
contribution to the world food program," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that China has accumulated some successful
experience in the agricultural field since the implementation of
reform and opening up.
</P>
<P>
The experience he cited includes taking agriculture as the
basis and giving top priority to agriculture in the national
economy; never slackening food production and actively engaging in
diversified operations; deepening rural reform and mobilizing the
initiative and creativity of farmers; implementing the strategy of
reinvigorating agriculture through science and education and
vigorously advancing agro-technological progress; steadily
increasing agricultural input and improving the conditions for
agricultural production; and opening wider to the outside world
and strengthening international agricultural co-operation and
exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Continues To Be China's Top Priority: President (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Along with the population increase, rise of per capita
consumption level and economic development, China's demand on
grain and other farm produce will continue to grow year by year,
the president noted.
</P>
<P>
"We shall unswervingly give top priority to agriculture in the
national economy, further stabilize and bolster agriculture,
ensure a sustained growth of food and agricultural production and
promote the intensive processing of grain and all type of farm,
livestock and fish products so as to satisfy the need of the
people," said the president.
</P>
<P>
There is every reason to believe that China has the capability
to get its people well-fed and well-clad through self-reliance,
and the quality of life of the Chinese People will be enhanced
gradually, Jiang said, citing as proof the country's "huge
potential for increasing agricultural output" and the "boundless
creativity" of the Chinese farmers.
</P>
<P>
The resolution of the food question, which bears on the
survival and progress of mankind, relies on the efforts of each
country itself and but it is also inseparable from extensive
international cooperation and exchanges, the president stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The developed countries should take concrete actions and
fulfil their due obligations in terms of capital and technical
assistance to help the developing countries enhance food
production capacity. The Chinese government, always attaching
importance to and taking an active part in international
cooperation in the area of food and agriculture, has made positive
efforts in promoting world's agricultural development," he said.
</P>
<P>
China and UNFAO maintain a sound cooperative relationship, the
president said, adding that the over 100 projects sponsored by the
organization in China have produced notable results and through
its "South-South Cooperation" Program, China has provided
assistance within its power to some developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to take this opportunity to express sincere
gratitude to FAO and Director-General Jacques Diouf for their
consistent support of China's agricultural development," Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
Citing an old Chinese saying "A country depends on its people,
and people live on food', the president called for new
contribution to realizing the goal of world food
security. "Mankind has a long and tortuous road to go before
resolving the question of food," he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
