<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 684 Companies Report Their Foreign Debts to Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A total of 684 private companies
in Indonesia have reported their offshore debts to the central
bank, Bank Indonesia (BI), a BI director said.
</P>
<P>
Miranda Goeltom said here Monday that 280 firms had complied
with the BI's instruction to report their debts last month,
official Antara News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, Miranda did not disclose the amount of the foreign
debts reported by the 684 companies.
</P>
<P>
Of Indonesia's offshore debts amounting to 133.687 billion U.S.
dollars by April 1998, 67.686 billion dollars were corporate
debts.
</P>
<P>
The huge amount of corporate debts is one of the reasons of the
depreciation of the rupiah (national currency). Therefore the
government is trying hard to overcome the problem by setting up
the corporate debts settlement team and implementing Mexico's
Ficorca system after adjustments to local conditions.
</P>
<P>
Mexico implemented the Ficorca program to defray the impact of
a massive 1982 peso devaluation on its corporations, by allowing
them to repay their debts in pesos rather than in dollars to the
Ficorca, which then paid foreign creditors.
</P>
<P>
One effective way to settle the corporate debts would be to
take stock of the debts, Miranda said, adding that the central
bank has distributed some 800 forms to private companies, but not
all have returned them.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia has therefore issued an instruction dated April
8 giving the delinquent companies time until April 30 to hand in
the completed forms.
</P>
<P>
A fine of 500,000 rupiah (about seventy U.S. dollars) will be
imposed on those who have not submitted their report after the
deadline for every week of delay, Miranda said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
