<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Calls for Reincorporation of Cuba Into OAS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Mexico called Monday for the
Organization of American States (OAS) to allow Cuba into the
regional bloc after shutting the Caribbean nation out for 36 years.
</P>
<P>
"The reincorporation of Cuba... will enrich the inter-American
system, generating major stability and harmony within our
continent," Mexican Foreign Minister Rosario Green said here.
</P>
<P>
Mexico and Canada were the only two OAS members that did not
break diplomatic ties with Cuba in 1962, when its OAS membership
was suspended due to ideological turfs with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the American countries have now resumed their
relations with Havana.
</P>
<P>
Her country, the top Mexican diplomat told a seminar on the
"Present and Future of the OAS," is against every attempt of
intervention in the domestic affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
"Any attempt to impose ideologies or models, no matter how
well-intentioned these may be, contradicts and undermines the
sovereignty of the countries," Green said.
</P>
<P>
Mexico opposes the exclusion and intolerance of the political
and cultural expressions that may be different from the majority
on the American continent, she said.
</P>
<P>
"The OAS should reflect continental plurality and diversity.
Respectful relations among different cultures and historical
traditions within our organization should be our best legacy for
the next century," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We have the opportunity to prove our capacity and political
talent to assert the principle of universality in our hemisphere,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
As Mexico's ambassador to the OAS, Green also urged the member
countries to fight against poverty and drug trafficking, defend
and promote democracy, push economic growth, protect environment,
promote trade liberalization and defend human rights in the region.
</P>
<P>
The OAS, which got its present name in 1948, was launched in
1890 as a forum for economic, political and social exchanges in
the Western Hemisphere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upcoming Chinese Navy's Visit to Australia is a </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The visit of Chinese naval ships
to Sydney, Australia, next week is unprecedented and also
reassuring, an international relations expert said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese navy's visit to Sydney is a symbol of the new
defense relationship that now exists between China and Australia.
It augurs well for increased stability and security in the
Asia-Pacific region," Gary Klintworth, a visiting fellow at the
Department of International Relations at the Australian National
University said.
</P>
<P>
The visit, scheduled from May 4-7 and involving three Chinese
naval ships and about 700 sailors, is the first of its kind by the
navy of the People's Republic of China to Australia.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese navy also demonstrate an interest in working
co-operatively with other navies in the (Asia-Pacific) region",
the expert wrote on Tuesday's edition of the Australian Financial
Review.
</P>
<P>
"To that end, the People's Liberation Army (PLA, or the Chinese
armed forces) is signaling a commitment to be more transparent and
outgoing than ever before," the expert said.
</P>
<P>
"The new openness (of the Chinese armed forces) suggests ... a
belief in the benefits to be obtained from neighborly exchanges
between the navies of countries in the Asia-Pacific region,"
Klintworth added.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Chinese ships, including a multipurpose
replenishment ship of 37,000 tons when fully loaded, a
guided-missile destroyer of 4,800 tons and a training vessel, are
scheduled to be open to the public in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The expert praised the move by the Chinese navy to allow public
access to their ships.
</P>
<P>
"This shows the increasing self-confidence of the PLA and its
willingness to try to develop goodwill with the defense forces and
the people of the region, especially influential middle powers
like Australia."
</P>
<P>
"The PLA, in other words, is going out of its way to engage in
the region in public defense diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
The visit follows Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian's visit
to Australia earlier this year, the first of its kind since
Australia and China established diplomatic relations in 1972.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
