<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Fails to Lift Sanctions Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations on Monday reached no consensus on lifting
sanctions against Iraq after day-long consultations, thus the
UN sanctions against Iraq will remain.
</P>
<P>
Before the consultations, the Security Council was briefed by
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)and UNSCOM on their
latest reports on the inspections of Iraq weapons in the past
six months.
</P>
<P>
IAEA said Iraq has met its demands by having destroyed all its
nuclear weapons, and UNSCOM said there was no virtual progress
made by Iraq in the areas of chemical, biological weapons and
ballistic misslies, especially in the area of biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reviews the sanctions against Iraq every
sixty days. This is the first review since UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and Iraq's Government reached the Memorandum of
Understanding on the inspection of Iraq's weapons on February 23,
which avoided possible U.S. military strikes against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
