<HEADLINE> US Governors Endorse National Dialogue on Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- About half of the governors in
the United States plan to endorse President Bill Clinton's race
initiative by devoting a day this week to getting the national
dialogue on race rolling on the local level.
</P>
<P>
The governors will support a one-day national campaign Thursday
sponsored by the Young Women's Christian Association (YWCA) as a
follow-up to the Senate's declaration of last April 30 as national
Erase the Hate and Eliminate Racism Day.
</P>
<P>
"The YWCA has had a long-standing history in this arena, and
the president's race initiative resonated with us," said chief
executive officer Prema Mathai-Davis. "It's not just dialogue, but
the next step, moving to create change in the community."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the number of participating governors grew from 18
to 26, according to the president's race initiative office. Eleven
governors planned to issue proclamations and 14 said they would
personally take part that day in activities such as panel
discussions or town hall meetings.
</P>
<P>
Former Mississippi Governor William Winter, a member of the
president's racial advisory board, said Thursday's events
represent the most significant effort by states to work on racial
reconciliation. Governors are crucial to ensuring that the
dialogue that Clinton wants is penetrating American society, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the governors are being low-key in their approach,
while others have taken up the activities with zeal, Winter said.
</P>
<P>
Besides governors, the mayors of 18 cities will take parts in
events that day as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
