<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hydropower Plant on Yangtze Tributary Passes State Assessment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Geheyan Hydropower Plant on the
Qingjiang River, a major tributary of the Yangtze River after it
passes through the famed Three Gorges, has passed assessment by a
panel of 120 experts appointed by the government.
</P>
<P>
The plant took 11 years to build.
</P>
<P>
The plant is situated in Changyang County in central China's
Hubei Province. It was jointly financed by the central government
and Hubei, to the tune of about four billion yuan (about 500
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Construction started on January 15, 1987. Four generating units
with a total capacity of 1.2 million kw have been installed. The
first generating unit started power generation June 4, 1993, and
the last unit was put in place November 26, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The plant, widely hailed as an experiment pioneering the
ongoing construction of a gigantic water control dam in the Three
Gorges area, has also survived huge floods that may occur once in
a thousand years. It has so far produced 11.2 billion kwh of
electricity.
</P>
<P>
In addition, completion of the Geheyan Hydropower Plant has
laid a solid foundation for developing hydropower resources on the
Qingjiang River on a large scale, according to Wang Dingguo,
chairman of the board of the Qingjiang Hydropower Investment
Company, which is responsible for development of the plant..
</P>
<P>
Wang added that two more hydropower plants would be built on the
Qingjiang River, with a combined generating capacity of three
million kw, in the years to come.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
