<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Make Amendments to Adoption Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some 440 Bulgarian children were adopted by foreigners last
year. Adoptions by Bulgarians were much more but there are no
accurate figures.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by the Bulgarian Association of Women
of the Legal Profession and the British Council in Sofia. It was
attended by Deputy National Assembly Chairman Petya Shopova,
experts of the ministries of justice, health care and education,
judges, prosecutors and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
The Hague Convention on the Protection of Children Upon
Adoption binds the parties to the Convention to set up such
centralized bodies thus guaranteeing the best interests of the
child, Roza Boteva, chairman of the Association said.
</P>
<P>
The Ordinance, regulating the adoption of Bulgarian children
by foreigners, guarantees the protection of the child and requires
applicants to have an adoption license issued by the respective
bodies in their country of residence. "We check whether such a
license has been issued and whether the adoption will be in the
interests of the child," Videnova said.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian legislation does not regulate control after adoption
but the Ministry of Justice requires post-adoption reports from
organizations or lawyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
