<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Election Failure Feared in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Commission on
Elections (Comelec) is expecting a failure of elections in certain
parts of the country which could thwart the proclamation of the
next president, a local newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are anticipating failure of elections in Mindanao.
Sometimes, we cannot prevent it. It can only be resolved at the
time of reckoning, " Comelec Commissioner Manolo Gorospe was
quoted by Philippine Daily Inquirer as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
This scenario, painted by Gorospe, is expected to revive fears
earlier raised by the opposition that the Ramos administration was
intent on holding on to power.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos must step down from office on June 30
when his constitutionally-mandated single six-year term expires.
</P>
<P>
Gorospe did not identify the regions or provinces where failure
of elections was feared.
</P>
<P>
But Gorospe stressed that if the number of votes in the
affected towns or villages was big enough to affect the results of
the election, there could be a delay in the proclamation of the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
Comelec sources said earlier this possibility was not remote in
the presidential contest, considering that the margin of votes
among the 11 candidates is expected to be slim.
</P>
<P>
Gorospe said partisan politics, insurgency, violence,
intimidation and coercion of election officials and voters could
result in the failure of elections in critical areas in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Under the election law, the Comelec can declare a failure of
elections "on account of natural calamities, violence, terrorism,
fraud or other analogous causes."
</P>
<P>
In the 1995 midterm elections, a failure of elections was
declared in 381 communities in the provinces of Lanao del Norte
and Lanao del Sur in western Mindanao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
