<HEADLINE> Japan's Four Opposition Parties Merge Into New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Four Japanese opposition parties
merged Monday into a new Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ) and vowed
to take power away from the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
The Good Governance Party, the Amity Party and the Democratic
Reform Party dissolved themselves within four months of their
separate launches and joined the DPJ, said a Kyodo News report.
</P>
<P>
DPJ leader Naoto Kan was elected president of the new centrist
party, now the largest opposition group with 131 seats at the
511-member upper house and the 252-member lower house.
</P>
<P>
The conservative LDP, led by Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto,
occupies 379 seats in the two chambers of parliament.
</P>
<P>
"We want to play a big historical role as the pivot for a
change in government," Kan was quoted by the Kyodo report as
telling an inauguration ceremony at a Tokyo hotel.
</P>
<P>
The new DPJ and other opposition forces might jointly submit a
no-confidence motion against Hashimoto's cabinet, said Kan.
</P>
<P>
Kan announced his new party's basic philosophy and policies,
under which it will pursue "a new road of the democratic center,"
or an alternative to free market and welfare state systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
