<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- It is a priority for China in formulating its foreign policy
to develop friendly ties with its neighboring countries, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin said in Beijing yesterday in talks with
President of the Kirghiz Republic Askar Akayevich Akayev.
</P>
<P>
No matter how the world situation changes, this basic policy
will remain unchanged, said Jiang, adding that developing
Sino-Kirghiz friendly relations and cooperation of mutual benefit
accord with the fundamental interests of the peoples of both
countries, and will promote regional peace, stability and
development.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing's preferential policies have attracted investment of
148 transnational corporations among the world top 500
transnational corporations. They have funded 400 projects in the
Chinese capital since 1988.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Visiting Chinese Vice President Hu Jintao said yesterday in
Seoul that China attaches great importance to the development of
good relations between China and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Acting Prime Minister Kim Jongpil, He
said the development of Sino-ROK ties not only conforms to the
fundamental interests of the people in both countries, but also
serves peace, stability and development on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
-- Local governments and Chinese Communist Party organizations
at various levels in north China's Hebei Province began to
confiscate mobile phones bought with public fund and held by
functionaries, their relatives or friends as a result of abusing
power.
</P>
<P>
In Shijiazhuang, capital of Hebei Province, more than 10,000
mobile phones have been confiscated by the city government. Hu
Tai'an, director of the Power Supply bureau of Luancheng County,
was relieved of his post because he abused his power for
purchasing 70 mobile phones for his relatives, friends and
subordinates.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will pay a visit
to China from Wednesday to Friday, at the invitation of Chinese
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, and exchange views with the Chinese
side on the preparations for U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit
to China and on bilateral and international issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese government urged Taiwan authorities to remove all
unreasonable barriers imposed on the direct shipping link across
the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the State Council's Taiwan Affairs Office
issued the call yesterday, while commenting on the first
anniversary of the opening of direct shipping service between the
two sides.  
