<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Offers Yugoslavia Carrot, Stick on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States will propose
a policy of carrot and stick to Yugoslavia at a Contact Group
meeting in Rome on Wednesday for cooperation from Belgrade on
Kosovo, a senior U.S. official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has often been accused of putting overwhelming
emphasis on punitive measures, so this time the U.S. has come up
with a package which includes both a substantial amount of
positive incentives," the official told a background briefing.
</P>
<P>
However, the official, who spoke on condition of not being
identified, declined to give details of the package.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group, which comprises the U.S., Italy, Russia,
Britain, France and Germany, would meet Wednesday in Rome on
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The senior U.S. official also warned that if the five other
nations, including Russia, involved in the meeting of the "Contact
Group" did not agree to the U.S. package, Washington would go it
alone on Yugoslavia policy.
</P>
<P>
Washington wanted the Yugoslav government first to devise a
"framework for negotiations" with the Kosovo Albanians and a
series of moves to lower tensions, then to start talks later,
said the official.
</P>
<P>
If Belgrade does not cooperate, the official said that new
sanctions will be imposed.
</P>
<P>
But he did not say what fresh sanctions could be imposed. The
Contact Group, which has threatened an asset freeze, has already
blocked trade and investment credits and had an arms embargo
passed by the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"It's the hope of the United States that we can reach agreement
on this strong substantive package which we have been proposing to
other countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we cannot, what we want to do then is begin to engage on
some activity, some more pronounced activity, on our own, on a
coordinated basis with the Contact Group countries," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said when Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and
Balkan envoy Robert Gelbard put the U.S. package to European
countries during a recent tour, the reaction varied, with some
reacting well and a couple "less than totally positively".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
