<HEADLINE> Georgian President Sacks Defense Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze fired Defense Minister Vardiko Nadibaidze on Monday
and named chief military inspector David Tevzadze as a replacement.
</P>
<P>
The decision, as the Itar-Tass news agency reported, was made
at an urgent National Security Council meeting. But the nomination
of Tevzadze, 50, is yet to be confirmed by the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Surviving the February 9 terrorist attack at the Georgian
capital of Tbilisi, Shevardnadze has asked the Ministry of Defense
to send fighter jets to convoy his plane's takeoff from airport.
</P>
<P>
However, Nadibaidze didn't take the protective measure on April
26, when the president left Tbilisi for a conference in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In response, Shevardnadze took the chance of a routine radio
speech on Monday to accuse Nadibaidze of failing to fulfill his
obligation of safeguarding the security of the president.
</P>
<P>
Nadibaidze's mistake was unforgivable despite his contributions
to the buildup of the country's armed forces, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nadibaidze had been serving as defense minister since May
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
