<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin America over the past few days:
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica has issued 200 million U.S. dollars in
Eurobond. The bonds are for a five-year term with an investor
yielding rate of eight percent, according to sources from the
treasury ministry.
</P>
<P>
This is the greatest bond package by the Central American
country to foreign capital markets and part of the country's plan
to reduce domestic debt.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that by the end of last year, Costa
Rica's internal debt totalled 2.63 billion U.S dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- During the first quarter of the year, the free
trade zone of Iquique (Zofri) in Chile registered an 11 percent
increase in total sales with a value of 505.6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Purchases made by Zofri amounted to 596.9 million dollars, an
increase of 30.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Peru's foreign reserves reached 10.45 million dollars
on April 22, surpassing that of the first quarter by 202 million
dollars, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The reserves will be enough to back up around 14 months of
imports for the country.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The 19th congressional session of the
Ibero-American Association of Liquefied Petroleum Gas (AIGLP)
began here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The forum will mainly address subjects including energetic
integration in the MERCOSUR (Southern American Common Market).
</P>
<P>
The AIGLP groups large distributing companies of liquefied
petroleum gas in Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Cuba, Chile, Spain,
Mexico, Paraguay, Peru and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama's state-owned sugar company "La Victoria"
produced 1.52 million quintals in the 1998 season, an increment of
149,000 quintals over last year.
</P>
<P>
General Director Horacio Rodriguez said his company also
produced six million gallons of molasses, 1.10 million gallons
more than last year.
</P>
<P>
The current sugar making season lasted 100 days compared with
the 87 days of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
