<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Far-Right Breakthrough Sends Alarm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A stunning breakthrough by a
far-right party at an eastern German state vote sent alarms across
Germany on Monday with politicians and commentators rushing to
search for explanations.
</P>
<P>
In Saxony-Anhalt's statehouse race on Sunday, the German
People's Union DVU, a fiercely anti-immigrant group of rightist
nationalists, achieved the biggest surprise by rising from
obscurity to win about 12.9 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest gains of a far-right party in any state
assembly votes in Germany since 1945, which also enabled the DVU
to become the first radical right party to enter a state assembly
in eastern Germany since the 1990 German reunification.
</P>
<P>
"This is a black day for all democrats," commented the German
Bild newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Describing the DVU as an "openly anti-Semitic, racist and
anti-foreigner party", leader of German Jewish community, Ignatz
Bubis, told the German news agency DPA that it was especially
alarming that the DVU had proven to have the strongest appeal to
young voters between 18 to 25 years old.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed Germany's mainstream political parties of not
doing enough to counter the rise of right extremism across the
country.
</P>
<P>
While admitting that the far-right surge in Saxony-Anhalt as
"unacceptable", Germany Chancellor Helmut Kohl told reporters in
Bonn that the DVU would have no chance of winning any seats in the
federal parliament in the national elections in September.
</P>
<P>
"Right-wing extremism does not pose a trace of danger for
Germany," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD)
described the success of extreme right in the eastern German state
as a protest against the broken promises of Kohl after the 1990
reunification.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "Germany's poorhouse", Saxony-Anhalt, which once proudly
regarded itself as a stronghold of heavy industry, now has
Germany's highest jobless rate, about 24 percent, the lowest rate
of economic growth, making a mockery of Kohl's promise of
"flourishing landscapes" in the East eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
The German federation of smaller enterprises BVMW on Monday
called the strong youth support for the DVU as "a disaster" for
the German economy and society.
</P>
<P>
"The lack of jobs and training opportunities has once again
proven to be the breeding ground for right extremism," the BVMW
said.
</P>
<P>
Many other German business groups also agreed that the success
of the DVU in Saxony-Anhalt was the direct result of the
unacceptably high unemployment in eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
They called on politicians in Bonn to break the current
deadlock on structural reforms and to improve the economic
conditions for job creation.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion researchers also attributed the Saxony-Alhalt
election results mainly to the widespread frustration of voters
about the economic situation in eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the Mannheim-based public opinion
research institute Wahlen found that the DVU had won much more
supporters from the jobless people than any other parties.
Meanwhile, about 64 percent of the voters said they were dismayed
about the economic outlook in the state.
</P>
<P>
"The election in Saxony-Anhalt was the first opinion test in
eastern Germany since 1994," said the Infratest institute in
Berlin, adding that "Its results have clearly shown that eight
years after the German reunification, the frustration about its
results has peaked and has searched an outlet outside the
established western German party systems." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0296 </DOCNO>
