<HEADLINE> Rates Rise Speculation Triggers Tumbling of  Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Pummeled by broad-based selling,
U.S. stocks finished sharply lower Monday as investors dumped
shares, driven by fears that interest rates may rise.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average plummeted 146.98 points, or
1.62 percent, to close at 8,917.64, recovering from a loss of
about 224 points suffered earlier in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Losers outpaced gainers by 2,890 to 313 on a trading volume of
693 million shares on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Other markets suffered heavy losses too, with the
technology-heavy Nasdaq Composite shedding 48.65, or 2.60 percent,
to 1,820.31, its third-largest one-day point loss.
</P>
<P>
The broader S&AMP;P 500 index lost 21.36, or 1.93 percent, to
1,086.54.
</P>
<P>
The stock market's sell-off was triggered by heavy selling in
bonds, caused by a Wall Street Journal report suggesting that the
Federal Reserve is likely to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1.65 points in price,
raising its yield to 6.06 percent -- its highest in almost two
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
