<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Senate Begins Final Debate on NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate began on
Monday a debate on the expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), which will lead a final vote on the measure
to add Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Senate press briefing, Defense Secretary William
Cohen sought to dismiss "apocalyptic suggestions" that expanding
NATO to include the three former Soviet bloc nations would poison
relations with Moscow, as charged by opponents.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the Russian government understands exactly what
NATO enlargement is going to mean as far as the stability for the
future," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that rejection of the three new members would
send a damaging message to Europe.
</P>
<P>
"For the United States, to now reject it would be very
destructive and cast a pall over the organization that would be
detrimental for years to come," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 100-member Senate is expected to vote on the measure on
Wednesday. A two-thirds majority vote is needed for the approval.
</P>
<P>
Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota, who
brought Cohen with him to his regular news briefing, said
rejection of the treaty modification "could send a tragic and an
extraordinarily damaging message to the European community and the
rest of the world about how the United States views its role."
</P>
<P>
Senator Jesse Helms told the Senate that arguments that the
move would antagonize and complicate relations with Russia were
"just plain wrong."
</P>
<P>
The NATO expansion would limit any Russian temptation to
restore its power in Central Europe, making Moscow more likely
to seek constructive relations with the alliance, Helms said.
</P>
<P>
"If anything, it will make it easier to maintain relations with
Russia because an expanded NATO will shut off Russia's avenues to
more destructive patterns of behavior," he noted.
</P>
<P>
But opponents of the move say that it would poison relations
with Russia and may lead to new confrontation.
</P>
<P>
"I think people in Russia feel betrayed by this," said
Minnesota Senator Paul Wellstone. "This is a very serious
mistake we are about to make," he added.
</P>
<P>
It is widely predicted that the Senate will be able to
approve the measure, which has been ratified by Canada, Denmark
and Germany.
</P>
<P>
However, a close vote was expected on a proposed amendment by
Sens. John Warner, R-Va., and Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., for
a three-year moratorium on further expansion.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of expanding NATO, a diverse and bipartisan group,
took their complaints to the Senate floor, calling enlargement too
costly to U.S. taxpayers and an unnecessary poke-in-the-eye to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
But Cohen stuck to the most recent Pentagon estimate that
enlargement would cost U.S. taxpayers about 400 million U.S.
dollars over 10 years, down from an initial Pentagon estimate of
2.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that since the initial estimate, it had been
determined that the three eastern European nations were in a
position to bear more of the necessary changes themselves.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cohen voiced opposition to the Warner-Moynihan
proposal to put a three-year pause on expanding beyond those
three nations.
</P>
<P>
While the administration has no timetable for further members,
to lock a decision into a three-year freeze would be unwise... and
counterproductive," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
