<HEADLINE> UK Announces Strategy to Curb Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Assets and profits seized from
drug barons will be used to fund the government's new 10-year
strategy to fight drug abuse, the British government said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the Commons, Ann Taylor, told parliament that up
to 25 million pounds taken from criminals would be channelled back
into the drug programs.
</P>
<P>
"It is right that the profits from this evil trade should go
back into tackling the problems it generates," she said.
</P>
<P>
Taylor was unveiling the government's strategy to combat drug
abuse, which is detailed in the White Paper called Tackling Drugs
to Build a Better Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Drugs are a major contributing factor to the crime which
undermines communities and gets in the way of progress and
prosperity," she said.
</P>
<P>
Under the government's new plan, children aged as young as five
will be taught the dangers of drugs.
</P>
<P>
According to government figures, almost half of under
25-year-olds have used illegal drugs and at least half of all
recorded crime has a drug-related element.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate there are between 100,000 to 200,000 addicts
in Britain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
