<DOCNO> XIE19980428.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Israel to Grasp Chance for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Monday urged Israel to grasp an opportunity to achieve its
founders' vision of peace with its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"Never has the opportunity been more real, and it must not be
lost," Clinton said at a White House ceremony marking Israel's
50th anniversary of statehood.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Clinton accepted an honorary doctorate of
philosophy from the Hebrew University of Jerusalem to
commemorate Israel's 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said David Ben-Curion, the founders of the Jewish
state, had set three visions for the Jews to fulfil. While the
first two have been achieved, "the battle for the third piece of
Ben-Gurion's vision -- a just, secure and lasting peace -- is
still being waged, and still in blood, and still in tears," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The president held out the hope that Israel and the
Palestinians could "close the gap" in the next couple of years
on stalled peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The event came a day after U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright expressed frustration at the logjam in the Middle East
peace negotiations, saying the process had entered a period of
"grave danger."
</P>
<P>
Albright is to meet separately with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on May 4
in London to discuss ways of reviving the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state signaled she is losing patience, and her
criticism appeared to aim mainly at Netanyahu, who has been
pleading for more time to decide on the scope of a West Bank
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"My message (in London) will be straightforward." she said.
"It is no longer enough just to talk, or to talk about having
more talks. We have been going around in circles for far too
long."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Vice President Al Gore, who also spoke at the White House
ceremony, mentioned he and his wife would go to Israel this week
to participate in the 50th anniversary celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Gore said he would carry "the yearnings of millions of
Americans for peace, for a new season of joy and a new jubilee
of hope" to the country.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Gore is to make another effort to get some
compromises from both Israel and the Palestinians after the
failure of U.S. special Middle East envoy Dennis Ross in his
latest mediation in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
